Parliament did not support an amendment to release Tymoshenko
The Ukrainian parliament today rejected a proposal to repeal the amendment to the section of the Criminal Code that condemns opposition leader Yulia Tymoshenko.
The amendment would open the door to the former prime minister's imprisonment, but parliamentarians rejected the proposal to reduce penalties for economic crimes in the second reading.
In October, Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison for allegedly signing a deal with Russia that was disadvantageous for Ukraine over the purchase of natural gas.
The verdict is not yet final, the appeals court has the obligation to review it in December.
Tymoshenko was convinced that this was a political revenge by the regime, and even in the West doubts have arisen about the impartiality of the court.
The proposal to withdraw paragraph 365 of the Penal Code that sentenced the former prime minister was supported by 147 deputies in the vote.
It required 226 votes to pass.
