Daily menu for an obese child: no breakfast and dinner with sausage
More than a third of children between the ages of 9 and 13 have problems with overweight, with overweight affecting 9% of the school population and obesity at 5%.
Most obese children come from families with unhealthy lifestyles, according to current research.
It demonstrates once again the importance of the environment in which one grows up for a healthy development of the person, as well as the models that serve as a reference.
At the table, for example, obsessive children eat sausages at least twice as often as children from normal-weight families.
For dinner, more than 19% of the obese had eaten chips the day before the analysis, which is linked to the prevention program "Obesity is not a coincidence".
In families with overweight children, there is no practice of playing sports, which is applicable to most families today, where only 15% of children responded that their parents, at least once a week, find time for physical exercise.
Survey of 900 children
The survey was carried out at the end of last school year and involved almost 900 primary school children from all over the Czech Republic.
It was the second edition of the program "Obesity is not a coincidence", supported by the General Health Insurance Company and the Unilever company.
So far, more than 12 thousand children from 4th to 8th grade have participated in the project.
A proper diet and sufficient exercise in the family are key factors that significantly reduce the number of overweight and even obese children.
"Only half of the children surveyed said they have five meals a day according to the diet: breakfast, lunch, lunch, snack and dinner, which is one of the basic conditions for a healthy diet", says one of the survey results.
No breakfast but with sausage for dinner
Specialists warn that in healthy development, details are also important, such as having a set time for family breakfast.
In the Czech Republic, however, only 23% of school families have breakfast at the same time.
In most families, each person eats breakfast alone.
But the worst part was finding out that 10% of households don't have breakfast.
Breakfast is, however, the basis of a correct daily diet.
The study shows that in families with obese children, insanity fries are consumed much more often.
Almost everyone - regardless of weight - drinks sugary soft drinks daily (70%).
In general, more than 40% of the children surveyed play sports, but this figure is reduced to less than half, just 15%, among their parents.
Make up your own diet
The next phase of the study enabled the selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to create their own diets from all possible offers according to their tastes and opinions.
"The dietary preferences of Czech children aged 12 to 15 years are far from ideal from a healthy dietary point of view".
Among his favorite foods are pasta, meat and sweets
"The popularity of sugary soft drinks is particularly alarming", warns the final report of the study.
The main food is the palm pulp, followed closely by the poultry.
Practically, children always reject vegetables and the taste for fish and vegetables is very low.
Changing to Healthy Habits
At the same time, the study shows that children are willing to change their eating habits if given the right information.
"In the control group of study participants, who completed the questionnaire after finishing the prevention program 'Obesity is not a coincidence,' there was in many cases a major shift in favour of the principles of healthy eating", the study results state.
The problem is that many children would prefer plain water to sugary drinks.
Children would also more often choose poultry and fish as their main meals on the questionnaire and restrict their consumption of sweet foods and flour products.
The stylist must also be a good psychologist, say the professionals
In the introductory article, How Stylists Learn, I already complained a little bit that the initial lessons were already quite loaded.
I had no idea how that was gonna go.
Lectures by three professionals in the field, how to dress problematic characters and, in addition, a seminar on how it works in the entertainment world.
And it's going to get worse.
The closer the final exams are, the more information and practical work awaits us
And although the course is held every Saturday and Sunday, it no longer fits a pin.
We've even studied with the principal, Alena, (in the course there is no man) about how to dress the woman who does not have perfect symmetry.
And so is the vast majority.
Someone's short-necked, someone's got a stylized figure without the right curves and someone's overweight.
The stylist must be able to smooth out wide shoulders, lengthen a neck or recreate the necessary curves
We've been given some tricks on how to make the body of women like Jennifer Lopez stand out, with huge breasts and hips but a narrow waist and at the same time not dress her in a way that's too defiant.
If, for example, the difference between your waist and hips is so great that your skirt or pants do not fit, it may be worthwhile to have at least one extra piece of fabric tailored.
You will not be sorry, for the clothes that fit perfectly are priceless.
A tailored skirt will feel much better than one that keeps moving, standing, dancing on your waist, etc.
The stylized body can afford to wear clothes with folds, ornaments, embroidery or draped.
There are certainly many different types of information and bodies, so I am glad that I have the whole week to put all this information in order in my head.
And even so, I'm afraid with the task at hand, I already have more than enough.
Each participant in the course has been assigned two celebrities, who must design two costumes: one for the day and one for the evening.
The current look, the fashion style that suits the person in question must be taken into account.
I've been asked to dress Miranda Kerr, who you may know from the Victoria's Secret campaign.
I scream inside, for me it's much better than, for example, Britney Spears or Christina Aguilera, who has recently put on about a hundred kilos (please note the exaggeration), or the very young Selena Gomez.
Dresses have to be cut from magazines or searched online and printed, then graphically crafted.
The moodboard, which is what the complete result is called, also expresses our personal style and our relationship with graphic design.
It is also important to think about the graphic part of styling.
The stylist therefore does not only dress physically, but also deals, for example, with product pages in magazines (concrete topics, such as trends, bags, coats, etc.).
We were told all about it by the stylist and designer Mario Kameník.
But all this is already left for Sunday.
The stylist has to have a global vision.
The three special guests cheered the Saturday conference with information on all kinds of bodies.
The stylist Honza Pokorný, the fashion designer Jakub Polanka and the fashion photographer Ben Renč.
Jakub reminded us that fashion is an illusion and the stylist should know how to take advantage of this.
And a good stylist knows how to work with the same garment in different ways.
Variability is, in this case, crucial.
Thus, such a trench coat can be worn classically with jeans and a T-shirt, but it also serves to dress the naked body with high heels and photograph it as if it were actually a dress.
Or you can just twist it around and pull it up your neck to get a totally different picture.
"Play with it", he urged.
The advice I value most is this: "To get started, you need to know all the rules first".
"You can break them later", said Jakub.
I finally get why we memorize all these formulas, what combines with what, why, if then it turns out that in fashion magazines we find different results.
Not to mention the parades.
Thanks to photographer Ben, I know a stylist has to have more types of clothes in stock than he intends to photograph.
So, for a fashion story to have ten pages (therefore, ten outfits), you have to have prepared, ready to use, at least fifteen.
And besides photos, the clothes work in combination with other garments, all of which are different from what you wear in reality.
All this must be taken into account when designing the outfit.
Honza Pokorný assured us that image and style alone are, in many cases, half the success.
Just look at Madonna, who is not exactly an extraordinary singer, but the image and marketing have made her a world star.
In the Czech Republic, for the moment, there is still no clear trend towards using the services of stylists.
Even famous people find it useless (my skills are enough, my physical appearance is not so important).
And when someone asks for our services, you have to keep in mind that they will most likely tell you a size that is very different from your actual (minor) size.
Then you just have to google and find out if the heart magazines have already written about the subject, if a certain celebrity has gained weight/thinned, etc.
On Sunday, Honza and Mario insisted that the stylist should not just be oriented in fashion, but also understand the outfit.
During your work, you must above all communicate with the people you see, so it is essential to be a good psychologist.
He knows how to value people, he doesn't make a fool of himself, he defends his opinions.
"When a director hires you to sort out her wardrobe and complete it with nice clothes, you can't just take everything and throw it away and say, 'Fuck, that's horrible.'"
"Find at least a couple of things you can consider and recommend for someone to wear", says Mario.
He himself also showed us that everything must fit into the so-called "placovka", that is, the work bag.
It's attached around the waist and you have all the necessary tools there.
There is also nylon thread (which serves the stylist during the photo shoot of products such as bags or hats), special clothes hook pincers in front, if it was larger (pincers and other types of hooks are not allowed, because they could damage the fabric), or a sewing set.
To avoid being passive listeners and to put something into practice, we have learned to put on the soles of our shoes.
Even during photo shoots in the studio, on a flat surface, you could damage the sole and even more so the outside.
And We did not make it but a covering and a covering.
We couldn't touch the shoes with the scissors so we wouldn't accidentally damage them.
So you had to be very skillful.
Mario has given me joy in praising my work without reservation.
I'm not really good at those skills, to tell you the truth.
This is just a small part of everything we've heard all weekend, in the second part of the course.
I've realized that pursuing styling professionally is not a smooth road, but I don't care what people say.
In Need for Speed: The Run, you race all over America.
The review
A journey, initially carefree, is complicated by a series of improper oversights of a routine journey during the morning shift.
I would like to say that I am very pleased that the Commission has taken this opportunity to make a statement on the subject.
The new installment, to which The Run is added to the title, raised high expectations even before its release.
It promised to give new air to the old Need for Speed racing saga and, as a result of what was shown, it appears as a game that should not end up being an action genre again.
We also felt curious about what the inserted scenes would look like, where the main character gets out of the car and walks on his own foot.
As is often the case with NFS series, the results did not vary much from what we expected.
There are races that can be considered acceptable, but in the total count you lose points because of absurd errors, which have been appearing in the series for years.
In fact, they cannot even be called errors, but are rather the incomprehensible reluctance of programmers.
The adventure starts off well.
You are introduced to a story, whose protagonist, Jack, has certain personal problems; to solve them, he is offered to participate in an illegal race across America.
You get behind the wheel on the West Coast in San Francisco, and your mission is to get to New York first.
The idea is to offer something interesting.
The route is divided into ten stages and then into more than fifty races.
This shows that each race is run on a different route and the stages are located in different environments, which are quite diverse and interesting.
That way, you don't even remotely feel like the game is always offering the same thing.
Some of the environments are even pleasing to the eye, although the technical level of the graphics is equivalent to previous installments of the series.
So it's not a big deal.
But a walk in the desert, the autumn landscape, or the high snow-capped mountains produce a very pleasant visual effect.
In addition, the careers are diversified from time to time by an atypical element.
So, for example, in the desert you encounter a sandstorm that diminishes visibility.
But in the mountains, you have to be careful not to get buried by an avalanche.
According to that, each of the races is very well developed.
There's only a couple of models, but that's enough.
For a moment, you try to outrun a required number of opponents (the normal thing in a classic race), then you try to gain time (classic timed duel) and then you are faced with a duel against a single opponent.
In the midst of all this, the police sometimes appear, which only makes things more difficult.
The novelty is the landscapes outside the car.
Interactive animations are presented when Jack, in most cases, has to escape from someone and you have to help him, always pressing the button just at the right time.
It's not complicated.
Surprisingly, however, there are far fewer landscapes in the game than you might expect (specifically there are only three).
But the end result is positive, because this element does not become annoying and, in the context already mentioned, is one of the elements that makes the game more interesting.
The driving pattern follows the footprints of the previous episodes.
That means that today it is not a big deal, but you can't say it's bad.
If you're looking for a realistic simulation, you can look elsewhere.
But a race designed with plenty of action suits this style of driving quite well, although we may find something better among the competing games.
So far, all is in order.
But problems arise after a while.
Unlike the correctness of driving models, the same is no longer true of collisions.
Games like this one can't be expected to recreate complicated warping and collisions, but in fact before a hit against any object, you can't predict how your car will react, so not everything is in order.
Typically, when you overtake a car too tightly or drive it through normal traffic, there are only slight friction, but in other almost identical situations, your car ends up doing uncontrollable pirouettes.
Or even end up totally destroyed.
Thanks to the reset system, no major problems arise, but it can make you feel bad.
The resets are programmed in such a way that when you suffer an accident or go off the track, the game returns you to the last rescue point on the track.
However, only five resets are available in each race.
If you consume all of them, you have to start the race from the beginning.
So it's just a help in case something goes wrong, but it's not very reliable.
Sometimes, even resetting doesn't help, it just helps to memorize the given stage.
A major disadvantage of the game is that the same events are repeated in different places.
In some curves, for example, you have to enter in a specific way; otherwise, they are impossible to take.
Other times you find yourself in a "civilian" vehicle somewhere always with the same configuration, even if you are first, fifth or arrive five minutes early or late.
This is especially irritating in situations, when you see two cars coming together in opposite directions, your opponent advances without problems, but when you arrive, you have to turn or brake.
It doesn't matter when you arrive, because it's programmed so that the surprise will always happen right under your nose.
The opponents have one more advantage.
Throughout the game, you'll come to places where, regardless of the timing, you'll always be outmatched by the same opponent in the same place.
And it happens at the end of the game, on a long bridge, which is even more shocking.
Your opponent must get there before you, no matter the cost.
When it's in front of you, it makes it hard to see cars coming in front of you, so you can start to eat the car.
You can understand the idea of creating a game with maximum doses of suspense and adrenaline, but the execution is so obvious that you're sure to be disappointed right away.
And it's a shame, because even though the travel model is simple, the game is fun and action packed, so it's often not possible to follow in detail what's happening or where.
And it really doesn't matter, whether the credit goes to the idea with 50 exclusive tracks or the qualifying in the race so it doesn't fit the boredom, or whatever.
An unusual idea is to change cars during races.
You have to be careful at the gas stations on the side of the road, because that's where you have to change cars, although in most cases you'll be fine with what you have.
Cars are divided into three categories.
Sports cars are suitable for urban areas, American strong cars for straight highways and exotic super sports cars for technical driving, for example, on mountain roads with curves.
In addition to the main storyline, there is also a parallel challenge, which is to say, there are races in specific places that you will know from the stories.
Here you will get not only medals, but also experience points for your profile, which is useful for both challenges and stories.
When the driver reaches the top level, several possibilities open up, starting with the car and ending with funds for the profile.
At the same time, an online Autolog function is connected, which compares your results with those of other players and makes other community functions available.
One of the hardest elements to understand is how the last race in history is done.
You drive to the subway tunnel (pass), where you start running through the dark tracks (pass).
The speedometer puts you between 150 and 200 km/h (pass) and suddenly the subway convoy comes behind you and takes you just ahead.
In the newsroom we will probably have a discussion about this for several days, about whether during the programming of the game no one thought even a little or if the authors really take us for a bunch of fools.
The technical part of the game is nothing extraordinary, but at least the overall visual effects result in most cases pleasant, sometimes even superb.
It is a pity that in the most tense moments the quality of the image is reduced and sometimes seriously.
This is particularly true in accidents where many participants are involved, when continuous image quality is no longer valid.
The audio is fine and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In order to appeal to the majority of the youth group, the soundtrack belongs to the "each one his father and his mother" category, but one can assume that no one would buy the game just for its music.
The final feel of Need for Speed: The Run is thus quite confusing.
If the game avoided absolutely stupid mistakes, we would have trouble claiming The Run is the best NFS game in recent years.
It feels like the game isn't over.
The fun is guaranteed, but prepare yourselves because mistakes will hit you in the eyes with the force of airport searchlights.
The choirs of the University of Carolina will participate in the concert "Students of Velvet".
The joint celebration of the International Students' Day and the anniversary of the Velvet Revolution as a musical experience will take place for the third time at the Festa Academica festival.
During the event, twenty choirs from secondary and university schools will be presented.
The festival revolves around two concerts on November 17.
"Carolina University has a high turnout for the festival".
The choirs are the Choir of the Faculty of Pedagogy and the Faculty of Humanities, the festival committee is headed by the Rector Václav Hampl", said the head of the organization, Jakub Čaloun.
The highlight of the entire festival is the free admission for all audiences to the concert of the high school choirs, which will be held on March 17 at 2 p.m. in front of the National Technical Library in Dejvice.
The program features the participation of Czech jazz musician Karel Růžička and his Celebration Jazz Mass.
In the evening, the concert "Students of Terciopelo" will be held at the City Hall in Vynohrady, with university choirs, including the choir of the Carolina University.
The Academic Festival aims not only to celebrate the International Students' Day and to commemorate the 22nd anniversary of the Velvet Revolution, but also to present choral music to the public at the highest level and to promote collaborative creation among young people.
The main organiser is the Czech Coral Union in collaboration with the Jan Kepler Secondary Institute.
All the events were supported by the Mayor of Prague, Bohuslav Svoboda, and the Rector of Carolina University, Václav Hampl.
The Festival will take place between 16 and 20 November between Prague and Pardubice.
The calendar offers, in addition to the celebration concerts, a whole series of musical events, improvised student shows and morning concerts.
Interested parties can find more information on the festival website www.festaacademica.cz
The Ambassador to the EU, Vicenová:
The Czechs have a reputation for being negative and Eurosceptic.
'The Lisbon Treaty has significantly affected the balance between the individual institutions'
"I didn't expect a war to be waged without a quarter".
"It will take five or six years before the situation has stabilized a little, calmed down and the new players have got used to their new roles", began the Czech Ambassador to the EU Milena Vicenová with conviction at her lecture at the Faculty of Law.
How could one not take seriously his slogan 'clear and open about Europe', which he said at the beginning of his lecture when he described each EU body and its relations with such precision and clarity, as would be the envy of many lecturers at the University of Carolina Law School?
Vicenová also reflected on the work of the new Permanent President of the European Council, Herman van Rompuy:
"The first criticism is that he is a foolish, grey official, capable of taking on any role, but I must say that he has left everyone bewildered, because he takes on his roles perfectly".
"He is a man who knows how to listen to the members of the 27 countries, how to communicate with them and who has a very clear vision of where the EU should go".
The new position of Foreign and Security Policy representative is explained by the question: 'Who is this EU? What number can I call?'
No one wants to ban us from Olomouc cheese
The European Council has been, is and will continue to be the agenda for the near future.
The Czech presidency two years ago was a success.
The Czechs dealt with the emerging economic crisis, solved the gas crisis and organized a summit for the Eastern Partnership.
The fall of the government at that time was identified as a very negative aspect, which seriously affected the Czech Republic.
The Czech representation in the EU is currently busy.
In the words of the ambassador: "a good uproar", not only the presidency, but also the financial crisis, which is being dealt with now.
On the other hand, the EU's seven-year budget must be approved, because the current economic situation is much more complicated.
If the budget is simpler and more effective, which sectors will have priority, which countries will receive the most support and which countries the least?
The Ambassador also recalled her main motto, with which she arrived in Europe: 'About Europe with clarity'.
"The truth is, I don't like ugly abbreviations, foreign words, or slang that people don't understand".
"How can a citizen understand that in Brussels cucumbers are not really invented - curved or round cucumbers, bananas of various sizes or that nobody is going to ban us from Olomouc cheese?"
It also aims to make more use of the EU environment and bring more Czech citizens closer to the European institutions.
The Europe of speed awaits us
The Czech people have a reputation for being Eurosceptic and people perceive the negative aspects rather than the positive ones, according to the ambassador.
He also regretted the low participation of Czechs in the European institutions.
The blame lies with a multitude of factors, such as the modesty of our candidates, their inability to write motivational messages, but also the lack of support from the Czechs.
In addition to the success of the Czech Presidency, he highlighted the strength and collaboration of the Visegrad Group.
"Believe me, when a Polish and a Hungarian come to me and a Slovak comes to me, a Frenchman next to me says, 'What, you guys from the Visegrad Group are already together?'
The EU is facing new and very tough budgetary policy rules for the Member States in the future, she said.
It is perceived as something very real of the two-speed concept, if not more so, in Europe, rather than the new "European Federation".
"We have countries in the Eurozone and countries outside the Eurozone".
"We have the Schengen area and we also have the enhanced cooperation procedure".
"It was said for the first time that only countries that want to cooperate and those that don't, stay out".
'These procedures will be increasingly used and will reinforce the two-speed Europe,' she hopes.
He also stressed the role of the Czech Republic and Herman van Rompuy in implementing the principle that all issues affecting the EU as a whole should be discussed between Member States, not just between eurozone members.
Brand story:
Innovative IBM enters its second century of existence
If someone were to look for a term that would very accurately define IBM's strategy, the most approximate would be "long term".
For the general public, IBM is the symbol of a technological revolution, a company that is perceived as current and yet has already passed a hundred years since its foundation.
The foundation for this long-term character was laid by the firm's first head, visionary Thomas J. Watson Sr.
He coined the slogan that many of the world's problems can be solved if people are willing to think.
Its slogan "Think!" became its hallmark, around which the life of the future giant will be built (it was also the title of an internal magazine that IBM began publishing in 1935).
Watson was also the basis of a carefully constructed company culture.
"For us, IBM means long-term thinking, a continuous movement towards the future.
IBM has survived and thrived for a hundred years for that reason, because it stayed true to its core principles, but not afraid of the changes around it.
That has allowed us, during our first century, to transform technology, business and society.
We hope to prosper even more in our second century", said the company's current director, Samuel J. Palmisano, during his anniversary.
A sophisticated system
Watson, already in the 1930s, was concerned about the care of his employees as the entrepreneur of Baťa in the Czech Republic (IBM employees were among the first American operators to enjoy paid holidays, insurance, elegant uniforms and a sophisticated remuneration system that rewarded the best inventors and salespeople.
The same long-term sophistication is maintained by IBM in the customer relationship.
From the very beginning the company was able to discover talent (as one of the first companies in the world to eliminate any kind of discrimination, it could choose without problems).
