The history of IBM: from the cheese cutter to space flight
The company IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York a hundred years ago, its original name being Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM was adopted in 1924 - originally a trademark used in the branches of Canada and South America.
The foundation for IBM came from the merger of four companies dating back to the 1880s.
He had inventions such as the famous "ficher clock", which allowed control of the entry and exit of employees.
The architect of the new company was businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who until 1930 also chaired its supervisory board.
Flint hired the head of a competing firm, Thomas J. Watson, to help him with the company's management.
The new leader eclipsed the founder of IBM (Watson's ideas remain the firm foundation on which corporate culture and identity are based).
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as the name implies, began with the production and sale of all kinds of business appliances, from meat and cheese cutters to cash registers.
During the first four years that Watson ran the company, revenue doubled to $9 million and the company began its great expansion across the continents.
Watson was so crucial to the company that, after almost forty years in the chief's chair, he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Jr.
Under his direction, IBM began work on the development of artificial intelligence and developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, IBM personnel and computers helped NASA guide spaceflights (to Mercury, Saturn and in 1969 the famous flight to the Moon).
Meanwhile, in 1964 IBM developed the first generation of computers, the IBM System/360 series.
The classic "fish", which established the standard of computers at the time, came to market under the name IBM 5150 in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, which in turn acquired the consulting part of PricewaterhouseCoopers and began offering a full range of high value-added consulting and services.
The strategy that IBM has paid for over the past three years is the concept of a Smarter Planet, that is, "a smarter planet".
It aims to make more rational use of technology, although areas have not yet been planned or conditions improved, for example in transport and city management.
For the retail sector, IBM recently introduced the "Smart Commerce" platform that enables retailers to manage the entire retail cycle.
IBM has a long history in this country.
In 1932 the branch was opened in what was then Czechoslovakia, the first country in Central and Eastern Europe to have such a branch.
Today, IBM ČR also operates the strategic outsourcing centre in Brno.
The headquarters for Central and Eastern Europe is in Prague, and there's also a world-renowned research team here that works with speech recognition.
