How travel prices have changed since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five authorised state-owned travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Travel agencies at that time sold in most cases only to the socialist bloc, as travel to the West was very restricted.
Czech tourists were therefore going on holiday to the beaches of the GDR (German Democratic Republic), the Soviet Union (Sochi in Crimea on the Black Sea), Bulgaria and Romania (both on the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A positive exception was the period between 1962 and 1972, when it was possible to travel to Yugoslavia, however, after the Yugoslav regime leaned westward and the travel of Czech tourists was then quite restricted.
A great paradox of socialism was the fact that citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. also Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely and individually even in socialist countries.
If a citizen wanted to travel individually, for example to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter, otherwise individual travel was not possible.
Travel agencies also offered trips to the West in those days, but one had to stand in line with a sleeping bag and stay that way all night, or have "good acquaintances" in the agency.
Still, not everything was won.
The so-called "promise of change" that was the condition for travel to the West was not granted to "politically unreliable people", who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency and, without a guarantee of exchange, it was not possible to obtain the resources (the Western currency) to travel to the West.
The vast majority of Czechs spent their holidays in their own country, so there were a large number of cottages and summer houses, which the Czechs acquired.
The way in which the Czechs travel has undergone a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 we were not going to spend our holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria, last year the Czechs made 4.5 million holiday trips to countries all over the world.
It is a great paradox, of which we are no longer aware, that the destination of choice, Croatia, was not free to travel to until 1989, because it was part of Yugoslavia.
The early 1990s saw the introduction of visa-free travel to neighbouring Western European countries, which led to a huge surge in short-term visits, especially to Vienna or Germany.
Czechoslovaks, for a long time, did not seem tired of excursions to the West, everyone wanted to see it at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris, groups of Czechs slept in tents in parks, since our income at the time did not allow us to afford a hotel or boarding house.
A typical characteristic of Czechs at that time was to take food with them (cans, sausages, etc.) to save.
Another important moment was the introduction of the convertibility of the Czech crown, so that our tourists could finally, after decades, freely buy Western currency.
Our living standards were rising and so were average wages, which around 1997 led to an increase in demand for travel.
With the increase in demand for travel, agencies began, from 1997 onwards, to regularly prepare travel using charter flights, which made travel prices incredibly lower compared to the past, thanks to the possibility of obtaining discounts on passenger volume.
By the late 1990s, the Czechs were traveling visa-free to almost all developed countries except the United States, which made our travel even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary tourism occurred back in 2000, when the first direct flight from the Czech Republic to an exotic country was organized, thanks to huge demand, and it was to Thailand.
Since then, direct charter flights with Czech tourists to distant and hot countries have been operating every year.
The exotic countries are currently visited by about 100,000 Czechs a year.
Another interesting moment of this era, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, came in the year 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the United States removed visas for Czech tourists, making our country one of the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, Czechs for the first time in their history spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history spent more than 15 thousand CZK per capita on foreign travel, including the costs of the place of stay.
