Peter Englund's intense and generous new book, The Beauty and the Sorrow: An Intimate History of World War I, "begins with a long dramatis personae of the kind that can make one's soul drop to its feet.
Here are some tips for action: Gently start this page and turn it into your brand pages.
You will get to know these people very well in Mr Englund's novel-telling, and this dramatis personae will function as your GPS, a beacon during those few moments when, like one of your men and women, you are confused and helpless in the fog of war.
Mr Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize in Literature.
What he has written here is an unusual book, which he describes, correctly, as "a work of anti-history".
It contains some notable names, important treaties, or famous battles; there are virtually no ambassadors, fancy journalists, or discussions of tactics or material.
It is not so much a book about what happened, he explains, as "a book about how it happened". It is about "feelings, impressions, experiences, and moods".
"The beauty and pain of battle combines the wartime experiences of about 20 ordinary men and women, on both sides of the war, from schoolgirls and botanists to climbers, doctors, ambulance drivers and administrators.
Some of these people will become heroes.
Some will become prisoners of war, or lose their limbs, go mad or die.
Their lives flash here like votive candles lit in a church; new ones are added to the mix while others are extinguished.
Mr. Englund's book is a deviation from standard history books.
It's also a corrective to the notion that World War I was just the disastrous trench war on the Western Front.
"The Beauty and the Sorrow of Battle" moves expertly through other theaters of war: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
Soldiers in this book are hit by beehives; you spend Christmas in Egypt under the pyramids; tsetse flies are an intractable problem.
This is a moving book, almost from the beginning.
War floods these people's lives like a natural disaster, a hurricane Katrina that stinks of cordite.
When artillery fire is heard in the distance, and you're a woman who's home with your children, do you stay or run?
Who's coming anyway?
Almost no one understands what's going on, or even why this war has to be fought.
"Lack of facts", notes Mr. Englund, "has been filled with conjecture, assumption, hope, fear, fixed ideas, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares and rumors".
"The Beauty and the Sorrow of Battle" follows individuals like Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, and Richard Stumpf, a young German sailor in the High Seas Fleet.
Her stories have been obtained in large part from memoirs, letters and other material previously published.
The explanations of their lives may be frightening or moving, but they are most alive in Mr. Englund's accumulation of small moments, missing details.
Many of these are about deprivation and coping with what you have.
She tells the story of a German schoolgirl: "Succeed them, everywhere substitutes".
"Coffee slip, fake aluminum, fake rubber, paper bandages, wooden buttons, and a few other things".
He keeps talking about the surrogate food in Germany.
It describes "meat made from cooked rice pressed in ram's fat (and topped with a fake bone made of wood); tobacco made from dried potato roots and peels; shoes with wooden soles".
There, he notes, "are 837 permitted meat substitutes in sausage production, 511 registered coffee substitutes".
Some stories are about honor and courage.
One American acknowledges his own drive for savagery and says of war: "You feel that, after all, this is what men are made for and not to sit on armchairs with a cigar and a whiskey, the evening paper or a best seller, and pretend that varnish means civilization and that there is no barbarian behind that starchy, stuffy chest".
A British soldier, on the other hand, realizes that he will probably die, and that no one will know or care.
"Once you resign yourself to the thought of self-sacrifice, you would like to think it could happen in front of an audience", he writes.
Rather, it is horribly like "a condemned man being strangled in secret".
Other observations are about an old Europe disappearing, and about new kinds of terror.
"The conflict has increasingly become an economic competition", writes Mr. Englund, "a war between factories".
It reflects the arrival of what he calls "a new species in the bestiary of the young century: The eloquent, ideologically convinced mass murderer in well-made clothes who carries out his butchery while sitting behind a desk".
People behave in unforeseen ways; there is both undignified and heroic behavior.
Mr Englund talks about soldiers who actively tried to catch a venereal disease from prostitutes as a way to evade service at the front.
"The most grotesque expression of this can be seen in the trade in gonococcal pus, which soldiers buy and smear on their genitals in the hope of ending up in the hospital", he writes.
"Those who are truly desperate rub it on their eyes, often resulting in lifelong blindness".
In this Swedish translation by Peter Graves, Mr Englund's prose, agile but not extravagant, is perfectly suited to his human task.
