After Steve Jobs died on October 5, there were some who compared him to Henry Ford - distinguishing the tech genius as the Great Modern Inventor.
But what Apple fans might find most revealing, in a recently rediscovered interview with Jobs that has been dusted off as a preview of a series of special screenings in major markets this week, is how much this creative mind understood about business processes and product workflows.
He was certainly a self-confessed designer, dreamer and hippie, but he was also a meticulous organizer and a junkie of flowcharts - a man who believed that many executives suffered "a disease of thinking that a great idea is 90 percent of the work... [but] there is a tremendous amount of work between a great idea and a great product".
In 1995, Bob Cringely was developing the television series The Triumph of the Nerds about the dawn of the personal computer, and sat for over an hour with Jobs for a long, rare conversation.
At that time, it had been barely 10 years since Jobs had been forced to leave Apple, and he was already working hard at his new computer company NeXT, waiting for the popular adoption of the Internet.
While a small portion of Cringely's interview was used in Nerds, he said the originals of the interview disappeared during transport.
It was only after Jobs' death that a complete VHS copy was discovered in the director's garage.
This slightly re-edited archival footage is the basis for Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview, a 68-minute film that hits Landmark theaters this Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known to hate in-depth interviews, Jobs here seems surprisingly willing to expose his technological philosophies and business strategies.
And very thoughtful.
At four different points throughout the interview, there are great silences between questions and answers - 10 to 15 seconds of reflections, where Jobs is clearly weighing his thoughts, seeking precision.
There are also times when Jobs' perfectionism comes to the surface, where he seems impatient because of Cringely's questions, pushing him to go faster toward the issues or arguments of greater importance.
Filmed before the era of Pixar, the iPod or the iPhone, there's something strangely prophetic about The Lost Interview, when Jobs evaluates what he sees other companies do right and wrong, and offers his own vision of the future of computing.
It's one thing to read posthumous reviews of Jobs' career, but there's something raw and inspiring about the Jobs we see here, the anxious dreamer on the brink of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can and should be.
Not long after I explained everything in detail here, he went and did it.
A quick summary of seven notable sequences from The Lost Interview:
About how he learned to run a business:
"Throughout my years in business, I always asked, ""Why do you do things?" and the answers you invariably get are, "Oh, that's just the way it's done".
Nobody knows why they do what they do, in business nobody thinks things through very deeply.
That's what I found.
Jobs goes into detail about his efforts to simplify Apple's accounting.
Puzzled by the way costs were recorded - often starting with a "standard cost" that was done on a case-by-case basis, and then adjusted with a "variable" - he developed an automated factory that he claimed could determine retail trade costs.
About the Pope joke:
Jobs narrates the "Blue Box" that he built with Steve Wozniak - a device that allowed people to effectively hack into the phone company and make long distance calls for free.
There's been a lot written about the device, but Jobs' euphoria here in describing the Blue Box as an act of empowerment is contagious.
He describes how he and Wozniak tested the box by using a pay phone, making a call, and then connecting from one AT&T network to another, while creating a loop with as many satellites as possible.
"We were wrapping things around the world a half dozen times and you were yelling through the pay phone and I was back a minute later at the pay phone next door", Jobs says with a chuckle.
"We were young and what we learned was that we could build something ourselves that could control billions of dollars of infrastructure around the world".
We two, we didn't know much, but we could build a little thing that could control a giant thing -- it was an incredible lesson, and I don't think Apple would have ever existed without it.
Jobs goes on to describe a glorious joke that he and Wozniak almost abandoned, calling the Vatican through the Blue Box in the middle of the night and requesting to speak to the Pope, while doing his best Henry Kissinger imitation.
As several members of the Catholic hierarchy were summoned in the middle of the night to speak with the American diplomat, the two burst out laughing just before the pope himself was awakened to answer the phone.
About falling in love with technology (and selling over the phone with Bill Hewlett):
At the age of 12, hunting for spare parts to build a frequency counter, he looked up Bill Hewlett in the phone book and made a call.
Shortly after their 20-minute phone conversation, Jobs landed a part-time summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
"That was a remarkable influence on me, it was the only company I had seen at that age and it shaped my vision of what a company was and how well they treated their employees".
Jobs later became one of the HP employees who visited the company's research labs in Palo Alto, where he saw "the first desktop computer ever made".
It was the size of a suitcase, had a small cathode ray tube screen, and I fell in love with it.
I'd get a ride to HP as a teenager and waste my time with that machine and write programs for it.
On improvising innovation:
At various points in the interview, Jobs talks about inventing new products on the go.
Early in his career, as he was selling a handful of motherboards, a customer asked if he could assemble the entire equipment.
Working with only 30 days of credit, I had to figure out how to assemble and deliver finished devices.
Later, while at Apple, he recalls the struggles he faced in developing a computer mouse:
"I remember having dramatic arguments -- they were yelling at me that it would take five years [to make a mouse that would cost $300], and I got fed up and I went out and found a designer.
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could build for 15 dollars and that was totally reliable.
On the big companies losing their strength:
Long before he led the Apple revival, Jobs predicted the way many industry leaders would stumble in his vision, and lose control of their market share.
"Say you work at IBM or Xerox, so you make better copiers and printers, and what?"
You have a monopoly of market share, so the company is no longer successful.
Sales and marketing departments increase success, so it's these kinds of people who end up running the companies and the people in charge of the products are pushed out of the decision-making forum.
The genius of the products that led to that monopoly position is rotting because of people who don't have the notion of good products vs. bad products - the knowledge of the necessary trade.
That's what happened at Xerox...
Xerox could have taken over the entire computer industry.
It could have been ten times its size, it could have been the Microsoft of the '90s...
They took defeat from victory.
On innovation as an artistic expression:
"There's a tremendous amount of work between a great idea and a great product... as the great idea evolves, changes and grows".
You learn a lot about the subtleties of it.
There are sacrifices you have to make -- some things you can't make electrons do, glass does, robots do, factories do.
You have to keep 5,000 things in your brain -- these concepts -- adjust them all at once...
In the end, it all comes down to taste -- it comes down to trying to expose yourself to the best that a team of humans has done, and then trying to adapt those things to what you're doing.
Picasso said that good artists copy, great artists steal.
We've never been ashamed about stealing great ideas.
What made the Macintosh great in part was that the people who were working on it were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians, who happened to be the best computer scientists in the world.
If it weren't for computer science, I could be doing wonderful things in other fields.
Scalia and Thomas have dinner with health care law rivals as the court accepts the case.
On the day the Supreme Court met behind closed doors to consider the politically controversial question of whether to accept President Obama's health care challenge, two of its justices, Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas, were entertained at a dinner sponsored by the law firm that will be presenting the case before the high court.
The occasion was last Thursday, when the nine judges met in a preliminary hearing to study the review petitions thoroughly.
One of the cases in question was a lawsuit filed by 26 states challenging the comprehensive health care reform passed by Congress last year, a law that has been a rallying cry for conservative activists across the country.
The magistrates agreed to admit the lawsuit to process and, in fact, a historic 5 1/2 hour plea is expected by March, and the outcome will likely further cloud the 2012 presidential race, which will be in full swing by the time the court's decision is known.
The lawyer who will appear in court and argue that the law should be struck down will likely be Paul Clement, who served as U.S. attorney general under George W. Bush.
Clement's law firm, Bancroft PLLC, was one of nearly two dozen companies that helped sponsor the annual dinner of the Federalist Society, a group that has been dedicated for many years to defending conservative legal principles.
Another firm that sponsored the dinner, Jones Day, represents one of the trade associations that challenged the law, the National Federation of Independent Businesses.
Another sponsor was the pharmaceutical giant Pfizer Inc., which has a huge financial stake in the outcome of the litigation.
The dinner was held at a Washington hotel hours after the court's preliminary hearing on the case.
Among the attendees were, among others, Mitch McConnell, the most prominent Republican in the Senate and a vocal opponent of the health care law.
The special guests at the dinner?
It's nothing new: Both judges have been attending Federalist Society events for years.
And it's not something that conflicts with ethical standards.
In fact, judges are exempt from the Code of Conduct that governs the actions of lower federal judges.
If they were not, they would arguably fall under Canon Code 4C, which says: "A judge may attend fundraising events from law-related and other organizations, although the judge may not be a speaker, guest of honor, or feature on the program of such an event".
However, the absolute proximity of Scalia and Thomas to two of the law firms in the case, as well as a company with a huge financial interest, was enough to alarm ethic activists in the government.
"This impressive breach of ethics and indifference to the code runs counter to the demands of several judges that the court abide by the same rules that apply to all federal judges", said Bob Edgar, president of Common Cause.
"The judges were entertained at a fundraising gala with lawyers who have cases pending before the court".
Your appearance and assistance in fundraising for this event undermines any claim to impartiality, and is unacceptable.
Scalia and Thomas have shown little interest in critics who say they blend the court's activity too easily with the agenda pushed by groups like the Federalist Society.
And Thomas' wife, Ginni, is a prominent conservative activist.
On the other hand, conservatives argue that it is Judge Elena Kagan who has an ethical problem, not Scalia and Thomas.
Kagan worked as the attorney general for the Obama administration when the first legal challenges to the law were filed in the trial court.
Her critics have pressed Kagan to refrain from seeing the case, saying she was too involved in upholding the law to be impartial for now.
Kagan has given no indication that he will.
Boeing receives a record order for $ 18 billion
Emirates is ordering 50 double-aisle Boeing 777s, with an option for 20 more.
Boeing also sells six Boeing Dreamliner aircraft to Oman Air, an operation valued at over a billion dollars.
It's rarely news when a company gets an order for 50 units of their product.
But it's a big deal when the company is the aircraft manufacturer Boeing Co. and the sale price for the 50 planes is a record $18 billion.
It's as big as the place where Boeing got the order from: the Middle East, a growing gold mine of future aircraft orders.
In a study released Monday, the Chicago company estimates that over the next 20 years airlines in the Middle East will need 2,520 planes worth $450 billion.
Boeing announced over the weekend its largest ever order for commercial aircraft by dollar value - 50 twin-aisle Boeing 777 jets.
The successful order came from Emirates airline in Dubai.
The airline also has an option to buy 20 more planes, which would bring the total sale price to $26 billion, Boeing announced at the 2011 Dubai Airshow.
Then on Monday, Boeing said Oman Air had ordered six Boeing 787-8s, the so-called Dreamliner, which boasts fuel economy and spectacular passenger services.
The sale price for six of them is over a billion dollars.
"This clearly has a huge positive effect for Boeing", said Morningstar analyst Neal Dihora.
"The quality of these particular customers is very strong".
Many Middle Eastern airlines are owned by their oil producing nations.
So not only do they have the money to pay for the planes, but an increase in fuel prices - usually harmful to the airlines, because it's one of the biggest costs - is not so harmful, because the country is making money from the rising price of oil.
That's important because they are less likely than other airlines to cancel or delay flight orders when fuel prices rise, Dihora said.
"They have a natural protection", he said.
The Emirates order solidifies Boeing's leadership in the wide-body aircraft market and helps to keep at bay the attempt by its competitor Airbus SAS to invade its dominance with the A350 passenger aircraft.
Boeing's win at the air show comes four months after Airbus said it would delay the debut of the larger A350, which competes directly with the 777-300ER.
It delayed the debut to add more momentum after customers demanded an increase in payload and range.
Boeing Co. shares are up 1.5% to $67.94.
The sister of the president of Mexico, apparently defeated in the vote in Michoacán
Luisa María Calderón claims that the narcotics traffickers helped her PRI opponent, Fausto Vallejo, in the gubernatorial race.
The sister of President Felipe Calderón appears to have lost her bid for governor of Michoacán during the violent state's election, and she claimed on Monday that drug traffickers helped tilt the race in favor of one of her opponents.
The preliminary results gave the lead in the race for governor of the western state to Fausto Vallejo, of the Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI.
"The intervention of organized crime during the entire electoral process and, especially yesterday, is alarming, not only for Michoacán, but for the whole country", Luisa María Calderón said in a radio interview a day after the vote on Sunday.
"They threatened our candidates, our election workers... They took over the ballot boxes, set up barricades... and ordered people to vote" for the PRI.
The PRI ruled Mexico for seven decades until it lost the presidency in 2000.
However, it is the staging of a comeback, and the victory in Michoacán is an important step in that effort.
The PRI is hopeful of winning the presidential elections in July.
Vallejo seems to have narrowly outran Calderón, who had led the polls before the election.
Calderón, a candidate for his brother's conservative National Action Party, or PAN, refused to recognize Vallejo as the winner.
Silvano Aureoles, the leftist candidate for the Democratic Revolution Party, or PRD, who currently holds the governorship, came in third, a major defeat for the divided and unfortunate left ahead of the 2012 presidential election.
Aureoles also refused to acknowledge the preliminary results.
Vallejo, former mayor of the state capital of Morelia, denied links to drug trafficking and urged the other candidates to accept the results.
Michoacán has long been dominated by drug cartels specializing in marijuana, heroin and methamphetamines.
It's President Calderon's home state, and he chose Michoacán to launch a military offensive against the traffickers in December 2006.
Yet the violence has persisted.
A PAN mayor was killed a week before the elections while campaigning for Luisa María Calderón, and numerous candidates abandoned local candidacies out of fear.
Although for the PRI, as unpleasant as the Michoacan elections may seem, a victory will help boost the party.
The man who is supposed to represent the PRI in the presidential election, Enrique Peña Nieto, speaking from Washington, congratulated Vallejo and said: "I think this victory should be very encouraging, for next year".
The BAsD urges Asia to help rescue the eurozone
The Asian Development Bank (ADB) has called on India and China to prepare to help bail out the eurozone from its sovereign debt crisis to avoid a long-term recession that would impede growth in Asian economies.
Rajat Nag, managing director of the Manila-based Asian Development Bank, said the world's two largest and fastest growing economies needed to "do everything possible" to accelerate the economic bloc's recovery either through the International Monetary Fund or directly through bilateral agreements.
He warned against the BRIC [Brazil, Russia, India, China] countries looking at Europe's difficulties in an "impartial" way and said that Asian financial assistance along with European leadership and resources would help avoid a long-term crisis in the global economy.
"We're all in this together".
"So anyone who can help Europe out of the crisis is useful", he told the Financial Times in an interview on the sidelines of the World Economic Forum in Mumbai.
"Asia may be protected to some extent, but it cannot be immune".
"So if China and India can help, let it be by all means".
The European Monetary Union has been severely undermined by a sovereign debt crisis in recent months.
In recent days, Italy's borrowing costs have skyrocketed dangerously and the prime ministers of Italy and Greece have resigned.
The current sovereign debt crisis in Europe has raised fears that it could push the world economy into recession and has generated calls for major emerging economies to come together to help the eurozone find a solution.
Mr Nag predicted that any support from Asia would be channelled through the IMF, but said bilateral assistance - such as the purchase of bonds from the EU bailout fund, the European Financial Stability Facility - offered greater bargaining power for Europe's Asian partners.
Anand Sharma, Indian Minister of Commerce, said that "India will do everything possible" to help the eurozone as its own economy was now suffering from falling exports and depleting foreign capital inflows.
"Nobody wants the eurozone to remain unstable and turbulent", he said.
"We have monumental challenges and we have to maintain a high level of growth".
"It's not an option, it's an imperative, because where do we find jobs for tens of millions of our young men and women?"
Others argue that developing economies like India have no responsibility to help rich Europeans when they face their own deep economic problems.
Ashutosh Varshney, a professor at Brown University in the US, said it would be politically very difficult to sell aid to Europe for India's 1.2 billion people, of whom up to 800 million live on about $2 a day or less.
"At some point they will realize that Greeks retire at the age of 50 and go on holiday to the beaches and that will not be good", he said.
Lee Howell, managing director of the World Economic Forum, also wondered why India's reserves should be used to keep the many well-paid Greek public sector workers in jobs of poorly managed, loss-making companies like the railways.
Mr Nag said the eurozone crisis threatens to have "important chain effects" across Asia.
The Asian Development Bank's forecast of 7.5 percent economic growth in Asia for 2011/12 now faces "downside risks" due to the threat from Europe.
He said vulnerable emerging markets needed to make "contingency plans" to protect themselves from a crisis and significant capital outflows from their economies.
Serious warnings from the Pentagon about possible defense cuts.
Defense Secretary Leon Panetta heated up Congress on Monday, warning that the impending automatic budget cuts could undermine national security and spark a financial chain reaction from the Pentagon hallways, to the battlefields of Afghanistan, to civilian assembly lines.
The Pentagon is already digesting $450 billion in cuts over the next decade, but now fears an additional $600 billion or more in cuts may be imminent if Congress fails to reach an agreement on spending.
"The impact of these cuts would be devastating to the department", Panetta said in a letter to Senators John McCain, R-Ariz., and Lindsey Graham, R-South Carolina.
He said that the failure of Congress to reach an agreement on the budget and its consequence, the so-called "sequestration", would result in 23 percent global cuts and a halt to many new projects.
"Such a large cut, applied in this indiscriminate manner, would make most of our naval and construction projects unworkable - you cannot buy three-quarters of a ship or a building - and seriously damage other modernization efforts", Panetta wrote to the senators.
"We would also be forced to involuntarily lay off many of our civilian officials and, because the reduction would be imposed so quickly, we would almost certainly have to fire civilians in order to meet the target".
"These changes would break faith with those who maintain our military and seriously damage the goodwill".
The cuts would eventually reach combat troops, Panetta said.
"While wartime funding in the Overseas Contingency Operations accounts is not directly affected by the hijacking, war efforts would be negatively affected by the severe disruptions in base budgets", Panetta warned.
"Personnel hiring would be reduced, leading to delays in contracts and contract oversight supporting the war".
"The payroll staff would be reduced, leading to delays in wartime supplier payments, and legal and political support would be disrupted".
The two senators had written to Panetta 10 days ago, asking for information on the possible impact of automatic cuts on the Department of Defense.
"The consequence of a hijacking at the Department of Defense would cause a rapid decline of the United States as the world's leading military power".
"We are firmly against this draconian action", the senators said in a joint statement Monday afternoon when they published Panetta's letter.
"This is not an outcome you can live with, and it is certainly not one we should impose on ourselves".
"The kidnapping is a threat to the national security interests of the United States, and it must not be allowed to happen".
Whether Panetta's letter and recent warnings from senators will increase pressure for a budget commitment or intensify calls to exempt the Pentagon from the cuts remains to be seen.
Panetta has been increasingly outspoken about possible cuts, even though he got a job at the top of the Pentagon with years of budgeting experience in Congress and the White House and knowing he was facing tough decisions.
At a press conference last week, the Secretary of Defense painted a grim picture of what might be ahead - an army with a shell, but no core.
"It's a ship without sailors".
"It's a brigade without bullets".
"It's an air wing without enough trained pilots".
"It's a paper tiger, an army of barracks, buildings and bombs without enough trained soldiers to accomplish the mission", Panetta said in his opening remarks at the Pentagon.
"It's a force that suffers from low morale, poor preparation and is unable to keep up with potential adversaries".
"In fact, it invites aggression"...
In an appendix to his letters to McCain and Graham, Panetta sets out new details of how the reductions "generate significant operational risks: delay in response time to crises, conflicts and disasters; severely limit our ability to be deployed and engaged previously around the world; and pose an unacceptable risk in future combat operations".
And Panetta said some of the biggest defense projects could face the axe, including those that are already being tested and some just in the early stages of planning.
That list includes the F35 Joint Strike Fighter fighter, a new planned bomber, the next-generation ballistic submarine, the new littoral combat ship and the new land combat vehicle the Army and Navy need to replace, the humvee.
Stopping development and further testing of the F35 could generate about $80 billion in savings over 10 years, but its supporters say it is the next vital step to improve and address potential threats from China and other rivals.
How to Spot a Lie
A glance at the latest headlines shows just how serious and pervasive deception and lying are in everyday life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy exchanging sexual harassment allegations with several women; each side accuses the other of lying.
Penn State administrators have been charged with perjury for allegedly concealing reports that a retired football coach was sexually assaulting children.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was "caught" with an open microphone telling US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is a liar.
Lying has destroyed careers and convulsed countries.
New York congressman and Internet exhibitionist Anthony Weiner made a mockery of his denials quickly refuted by irrefutable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been charged with campaign finance violations related to the cover-up of an extramarital affair.
And again, no one who lived through it will ever forget the media circus unleashed by President Bill Clinton when he lied during his second term about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
Legends about cheating on school and college exams are widespread.
There have been cases where teachers have given the test answers to students in order to be better seen in their performance assessments.
Mentors who should be teaching the opposite are sending the message that lying and cheating are acceptable.
How much of a hoax are we finding?
On any given day, studies show that you can be lied to anywhere from 10 to 200 times.
Sure, a lot of those lies are godly lies.
Another study showed that strangers lied three times in the first 10 minutes of meeting.
Lying detection, or "lying tracking", is an essential skill that we all must acquire, for both personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a board game like, say, Charade, where the goal is to exclaim, "I've got you", cheat detection is a branch of serious knowledge based on scientific data obtained over the past six decades at prestigious universities that have conducted in-depth research projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the research is that the old myths about lying have been debunked.
Liars do look you in the eye.
They don't always stutter, babble, blush, or get restless.
Nor can it be concluded that liars are difficult to detect or unmask.
A trained polygraph can get to the truth by learning about the statement structure, microfacial expressions, question formations and timing.
I spent several years probing scientific discoveries about deception in the vast and ever-emerging body of knowledge, and it was clear that deception detection is a modern technique that is easy to learn and helps navigate our complex world - especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviewing, or negotiation management.
Good liars have the ability to read others well, make them feel at ease, manage their own emotions, and intuitively sense how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men tell more "self-directed" lies, while women tell more "others-directed" lies -- usually to protect someone's feelings -- that married people lie to their partners less often than unmarried people (but the lies they usually tell tend to be "huge").
We also know that if you are perceived as a wrongdoer, others will feel less guilty about lying to you.
How do you know if someone's lying?
First, observe the subject's usual behavior.
This is called "creating a baseline".
It helps to provide reference points for measuring changes later.
Notice the subject's posture, laughter and vocal characteristics.
You better know if someone normally kicks your foot all the time so you don't make unfair accusations when you see your feet kicking in the middle of the meeting.
Next, look for groups of deceptive behaviors, verbal and nonverbal.
Consider these behavioral groups as warning signs, not proof of deception.
People who cheat may freeze their upper body trying to remember their story, may point their feet toward the door, lean toward an exit, change their posture significantly, or exhibit a "post-interview gasp" -- that exaggerated sigh of relief and change of posture once all the difficult questions are over.
Often the interrogators make it seem that the interview is over just to seek that post-interview relief.
He also pays attention to the subject's vocabulary.
Scott Peterson went all out and used the time spent claiming his murdered wife was alive, launching a nationwide manhunt.
Cheating people may also use distancing language: "I did not have sex with that woman... Miss Lewinsky" or repeat a difficult question entirely.
The most common verbal cues are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "restrictive language" when answering a difficult question: "Well... to be honest... as far as I'm... aware".
This makes the response a perception rather than a fact and is often a warning sign.
There is no magic formula for detecting lies, but developing skills to detect deception is possible.
These skills will improve anyone's chances of avoiding being victimized by scam artists in their professional and personal lives.
The controversial pipeline plan diverted after the threat of US delay in approval
Days after the Obama administration threatened to delay approval of a planned pipeline from Canada to the Gulf of Mexico -- infuriating unions, while appeasing environmentalists -- the company seeking to build the pipeline says it is willing to redirect the project to get back on track.
TransCanada said Monday night it will move the planned pipeline out of the ecologically sensitive Sandhills area in Nebraska, and is confident the project will win approval.
The company announced the decision at a press conference at the Nebraska State Capitol.
TransCanada's executive, Alex Pourbax, says the company remains confident that the pipeline will eventually be approved, though it is true that it will be on a different route.
This comes after the State Department announced last week that it would delay a decision on a federal permit for the project until new potential routes that bypass areas of the Nebraska Sandhills and the Ogallala Aquifer, a vast underground water supply, are studied.
"This is a real road to progress", Rep. Lee Terry, a Republican from Nebraska, told Fox News.
The new environmental review ordered by the State Department may set aside any decision until 2013, after next year's election, though officials denied that politics was involved in the decision.
Obama, in a written statement last week, described the decision as the request of the State Department, and expressed their full support.
The 1,700-kilometer pipeline would run from Canada to the Gulf of Mexico.
It would carry 700,000 barrels a day from the province of Alberta to refineries in Texas.
To do that, you'd have to cross six states.
It is hated by environmentalists, but loved by working groups, who have bet on the estimated 20,000 jobs linked to the pipeline.
But Nebraska lawmakers opposed to the plan are weighing legislation to force a move away from the Sandhills region and the Ogallala aquifer, the largest source of drinking water and irrigation.
The State Department's current environmental impact study found that the project only posed limited adverse environmental impacts, but the energy industry source said the department's inspector general has ordered an independent test of the review process, focusing on two issues.
One is whether the lobbyist hired by TransCanada, Paul Elliot, who was a campaign adviser to Hillary Clinton in 2008, represents a conflict of interest for the program.
The other is whether a firm that was hired to run the original studio was an inappropriate choice because it was linked to TransCanada.
Patti LaBelle sued for allegedly causing a child to throw up in fear.
A New York family claims that disco music diva Patti LaBelle behaved like a crazy person in the lobby of her Manhattan apartment building, terrifying her young daughter to the point that she threw up in fear.
The "Lady Marmalade" singer's rant scared 18-month-old Genevieve Monk so much that she suffered "personality changes, sleep disturbances" and "increased fear of strangers", her family says in Manhattan Superior Court.
It was November 10th of last year when streetcar driver Kevin Monk, his wife, Roseanna, a kindergarten teacher, and Genevieve were preparing to go on a family trip.
While Kevin Monk was getting in the car, Roseanna Monk went down to the lobby of the Riverside Boulevard building, with her luggage, taking Genevieve.
Roseanna Monk said she stood near the door and put her daughter on the floor for a moment.
"Someone came up behind me and said, 'Do you know what your daughter is doing?' I said, 'Yes,' and I went to pick her up", he said.
LaBelle angrily rebuked the pregnant woman.
"He said in an aggressive tone, 'You shouldn't have left your daughter near the door,'" Roseanna Monk said.
I said, "I have no interest in what you say or think".
He got angry and started using bad words - the C word and the J word out loud...
He had a bottle of water and he started throwing the water from the bottle at me".
He said Genevieve got hysterical.
"I said to this woman, 'Look what you've done to my daughter,'" said the girl's mother.
LaBelle leaped on the mother -- who was still holding Genevieve -- and had to be held back by her surroundings and pulled into a waiting car, Roseanna Monk said.
The little girl was crying so hard she threw up, he added.
Later, the family sent a note asking for an apology from LaBelle, but received no response.
LaBelle's lawyer and representatives have not returned calls to comment on what happened.
The lawsuit seeks unspecified damages, but the family's lawyer, Sam Davis, said he took the case for free and the family plans to donate all the money he makes to a children's cancer support association.
"The purpose is to hold Patti LaBelle accountable for her behavior", Davis said.
"That kind of behavior is completely unacceptable, especially when directed at a kindergarten teacher who is holding an 18-month-old child".
Climate adversity slowed the economy
During the first year of Mario López Valdez's administration, in Sinaloa unemployment and informality have increased, foreign investment has fallen and the economy has contracted.
2011 is a year that will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa, it is the first year of the government of Mario López Valdez, self-styled change, which generated great expectations regarding the progress in the economy, but given the climatic adversity of the beginning of the year, there is no growth, but instead there is a deterioration in the main indicators of economic development.
The low temperatures in February, in addition to causing millions of losses for the agricultural sector, limited the possibilities of the state economy to grow, caused a contraction of economic activity in general of 3.6 percent in the first half of the year, mainly justified by the historic fall of 31.16 percent in agriculture, which affected the dynamism of the other economic sectors.
According to the report of affectations by frosts, issued by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, there were damages in 582 thousand 835 cultivated hectares, of which 78.03 percent suffered total damage and the remaining 21.07 percent had partial damage, the main crops affected were vegetables, maize and garbanzo.
The fall in economic activity has generated, until November, a steady increase in unemployment in the state, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography the state unemployment rate during the first three quarters of the year was observed to grow rapidly, as while from January to March 55 thousand 053 Sinaloenses were unemployed, with a rate of 4.53 percent of the Economically Active Population, for the second quarter the rate went to 5.28 percent, and between July and September the average continued to increase to 6.19 percent, a rate that in number of people throws more than 74 thousand unemployed, an increase compared to the first half of 18 thousand 969 individuals.
Less liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is multifactorial, for the economist Gerardo López Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the growth of unemployment can be explained indirectly, depending on the actions that have been carried out since public policy.
"What we are seeing is a growth in unemployment that has to do with several factors, including the loss of liquidity in the market due to a restriction of resources by the legislation that was approved in the congress to combat money laundering, and for people who grab dollars illegally it is not easy for them to work, invest and use them in something", he said.
Migration stopped
López Cervantes pointed out that in the increase in unemployment there is also a demographic factor.
"The number of people leaving the state looking for work abroad, in the United States has been restricted, first by the difficulties of entering, and second because entering they already have many difficulties to find work, those people are staying and are demanding sources of work here in the state, which makes unemployment rise", he said.
Informal use
The analysis of the Sinaloese labour market is aggravated by the high level of informality that prevails among the working conditions, according to INEGI, 60.38 percent of the employed population in the state works without being co-paying as a worker to any social security institution.
In addition to unemployment and informality, another of the labor lags of the state are low wages, the entity has the lowest salaries in the country, according to the records of the Mexican Institute of Social Security and the Secretariat of Labor and Social Security.
The average monthly income of Sinaloenses workers was, until September, 5 thousand 352 pesos, far below the national average, located at 7 thousand 375 pesos.
FDI contraction
In addition to the fall in economic activity and the increase in unemployment, during 2011 the greatest decrease in Foreign Direct Investment of the last 10 years was recorded, according to the Secretariat of Economy from January to June the state IED amounted to 630 thousand 697 dollars, which represents a fall of 87.74 percent compared to the 5 million 143 thousand 312 dollars recorded during the same period of the previous year.
The State Government's Economic Development Secretariat, meanwhile, accounts for a total investment of 17 billion 280 million pesos in the year, mainly from companies in the tertiary sector.
The Debt
In view of the economic contraction, the state government requested in July to the state congress the approval of a credit for 3 billion pesos, which would be intended for investment in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities, in order to reactivate the economy, the approval of the local congress was for an amount of 2 billion 600 million pesos, and until November have not observed the benefits of indebtedness in any sector of the state economy.
Reactions
For business representatives, the first year of Mario López Valdés's government shows a lack of government management capacity.
Miguel Loredo López, president of the National Chamber of the Transformation Industry, said that during 2011 there was a lack of harmonization of the wills of the various sectors, including the state government itself.
"The performance of the economy in Sinaloa during this year has been really very poor, we have to work intensely to recover the ground we lost this year, in 2012 we have to redouble efforts, lacked align the effort of all and above all the good march already synchronized of this new team of Government, we hope that next year will be much better", he said.
Economic slowdown
Loredo López said events like the frosts of early this year stopped the state economy and restricted its performance and growth.
"The low economic flow is the product of several events, including frosts, one of the main effects has been a slow economy that does not turn around fast enough to generate an economic dynamism that allows to have an acceptable level of flow in processes, products and services and therefore, at the end of the year we are closing much below the expectations we had", he said.
Redefining vocation
For Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Confederation of Patronal of the Mexican Republic in Sinaloa, he said that it is required to accuse the state towards productive activities of greater dynamism.
"In general terms we have observed that it has been working, we believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term program in which the vocation and economic direction of the state is redefined, because it is important that all the potential of the material and human resource that Sinaloa has is detonated", he said.
Work to be done
The Coparmex president stressed the importance of establishing a future vision that better aligns the Government's efforts.
"In general terms I would say that the Government has been striving to give good results in different matters, in terms of economic development there are some advances but it is important that a long-term program is developed", he said.
He noted that the current administration has shown progress in its way of conducting public policy.
"There are elements that allow us to say that the Government is being more inclusive, I can say that there is work done and I think the Government is aware that there is work to be done", he said.
