Court rules "analog off" in Mexico in 2015
The replacement of analogue signals by digital ones is one of the most important changes the world has seen in recent years.
The Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) dismissed the constitutional controversies that the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies have brought against the presidential decree that advances the so-called "analogic blackout" from 2021 to 2015, as the eight votes needed to invalidate it did not come together.
A minority of four ministers, including the president of the Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his powers by issuing the decree detailing the actions to be followed to concretise the transition to digital terrestrial television.
With that result, the constitutional controversy promoted by the Senate of the Republic was dismissed for not reaching the qualified majority of eight votes for the Court to pronounce on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the decree, and it remains in force.
The draft judgment, drafted by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed declaring the decree unconstitutional, because the regulation of radio and television matters is a faculty reserved by law to the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in contravention of the principles of hierarchical subordination and law reserve.
The project was supported by Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero herself.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies promoted two constitutional controversies to challenge the decree, and by admitting the demands, Minister Sánchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all actions in it arranged for the digital transition.
The plenum of ministers also decided to dismiss the demand put forward by the Chamber of Deputies, without entering into the discussion of the project, also by Minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his speech, the minister-president said he did not agree with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the federal Executive cannot structure through general rules the measures for public administration to prepare.
"Neither do I think that if I did it would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body", and he recalled that planning public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector correspond to the Federal Executive, who has as a constitutional mandate, the rectorate of the State.
The replacement of analogue signals by digital ones is one of the most important changes the world has seen in recent years, and it results in better use of the radio spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
Postponing the change, he said, would be postponing the benefits of digitalisation, which implies a decision of public interest, which does not have only a technical dimension, "since it covers economic, social, political and national security issues".
These issues, he stressed, "require the operation of the entire established system, in accordance with the principle of economic rectorage of the State, includes a group of attributions that the Constitution leads to the faculty of the State Executive".
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world have already completed the digital transition, and have done so through the Executive, despite having highly specialized technical bodies.
He said the executive, by issuing the decree, is not in any way invading the sphere of Congress's powers, as it is providing in the administrative sphere for the observance of laws issued by the Legislature.
They analyze the possibility of a count "vote by vote" in Michoacán
According to the data released by the PREP, the difference between first and second place in the governor election is just 27 percent, even without counting the votes for 879 of the 6 thousand 74 total acts.
The possibility of counting "vote by vote" is a reality in the electoral process this year in Michoacán, where according to the data released by the Program of Electoral Results Preliminary (PREP) the difference between first and second place in the election of governor is just 27 percent, even without counting the votes corresponding to 879 of the 6 thousand 74 total acts.
In this regard, the president of the General Council of the Electoral Institute of Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, just last November 9, the electoral body approved a series of guidelines in order to harmonize local norms with the federal reform in electoral matters.
As you may recall, Michoacán did not homologate its Political Constitution nor its Electoral Code of the State or its Law of Electoral Justice, since the State Congress approved the reforms shortly before the end of the legal term so that they could come into force in the present electoral process and the governor Leonel Godoy Rangel omitted its publication in the timeframe provided for in the Law of the Official State Periodical, with the argument that he had some objections.
On November 9, the Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) resolved the constitutional controversy promoted by the local Legislative Power and called the state's vote on constitutional reforms "invalid and illegal", since it has no right to "sanction or veto them".
Interviewed about the possibility of "voting by vote", María de los Ángeles Llanderal said that thanks to the approval of the corresponding guidelines by the General Council of the IEM it will be possible to carry out partial and total counting of the vote by the local electoral body.
In this way, the partial counting of votes in one or more electoral packages may be carried out if the results of the minutes do not coincide, the minutes of vote and counting are not in the file of the box or are not in the possession of the president of the box, or if there are errors or obvious alterations in the minutes.
In addition, the total number of votes received in all polling stations may be counted when there is evidence that the difference between the candidate presumed to have won the election in question and the candidate who has obtained second place in the vote is equal to or less than one percentage point, provided that at the beginning of the sitting there is an express request from the representative of the party and/or coalition that nominated the second of the nominated candidates.
The total vote may also be counted if at the end of the ordinary count it is established that the difference between the presumed winner and the second-place candidate is equal to or less than one percentage point, provided that there is an express request from the representative of the political party whose candidate came in second place, in which case the electoral packages that have been the subject of partial counting shall be excluded.
It should be noted that in this situation is the election of Morelia, where according to the PREP the difference between first and second place is just 0.16 percent, although without counting the votes of 129 of the 923 total acts.
