The new Italian government will be formed on Wednesday.
The appointed Prime Minister, Mario Monti, will meet tomorrow with the President of Italy to present the new government that will face a crisis that has put that country on the brink of economic disaster.
Italy's newly appointed prime minister, Mario Monti, will meet with the president of Italy on Wednesday to present the new government that will face a crisis that has put Italy on the brink of economic disaster and endangered the entire eurozone.
A statement from the presidential palace announced that Monti, named Sunday, will meet Wednesday with President, Giorgio Napolitano, to confirm he can form a government.
He is expected to present a cabinet made up mostly of technocrats, although it is unclear when the new executive will take office.
Monti said he will present to the president the outcome of his talks with the political parties in his attempt to form a government.
The Commission has also been asked to provide a list of the countries which will be eligible for the EU's assistance.
Monti did not explicitly say he would be able to form a government but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles have been overcome.
The 'framework is now well delineated', he added.
Monti has completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, far less than normal, as Italy battles a political and financial crisis that has pushed its debt costs to unsustainable levels.
The new administration led by former European Commissioner Monti must approve a tough austerity package demanded by European leaders to restore battered confidence in Italy.
Underlining the pressure on Monti to act quickly, market instability put the yield on Italian 10-year BTP bonds above 7%, the level at which Greece and Ireland were forced to be bailed out.
Emma Marcegaglia, leader of the Italian employers' Confindustria, told the press after meeting with Monti: "We said we would support this government a lot".
We believe that this government is the last chance for Italy to get out of this emergency situation.
Monti's chances of success were boosted considerably by the backing of Silvio Berlusconi's PDL party, which the crisis forced to resign on Saturday.
"We believe that Professor Monti's efforts are destined to have a good result", said Angelino Alfano, secretary of the centre-right party.
The support of the PDL, Italy's largest party, is significant because so far many of its members had opposed the technocratic majority government that Monti is forming.
Parliamentary support
The new Monti government must have strong parliamentary support to implement what are likely to be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blockage or delay in their efforts could trigger a new and devastating attack on the financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign banks added to the pressure by warning that a failure of Monti would be a disaster.
Monti began on Monday consultations with political parties, trade unions and business groups, as well as youth and women's organisations.
He'll end his round of meetings Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by Napolitano, who has enabled an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief respite at the end of last week when it became clear that Berlusconi would resign, the costs of Italy's debt have now returned to critical levels amid uncertainty over whether the new prime minister will succeed.
Bailing out Italy, with a public debt of 1.8 trillion euros, would be too much for the eurozone's current financial defenses.
Monti has said his government should last until the next elections, scheduled for 2013, despite widespread predictions that politicians will only give him time to implement reforms before elections are brought forward.
Monti has said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the major parties insist it should be made up of only technicians, an indication of his reservations about a process forced by financial pressure.
Political sources pointed out that mutual distrust and disagreements between the parties are complicating the attempt to include political figures.
