Quintet included the country in its two-decade tour
"Going to Costa Rica is a dream come true"
In an exclusive interview with Viva, Pearl Jam bassist Jeff Ament said the band is ready to perform one of their best shows yet next Sunday at the National Stadium.
It's been over 20 years of waiting, but the band says that for them too it will be a dream come true to play in the country.
This was confirmed by bassist and founding member, Jeff Ament, who spoke exclusively with Viva from Brazil last week.
The group is on the South American side of their two-decade tour and will make their only stop in Central America on Sunday.
They will perform at the National Stadium, starting at 7:30 p.m., along with the angeline band The X and the nationals of Las Robertas.
This is an excerpt from the conversation, the full transcript of which is at The Nation on the Internet.
For their Costa Rican fans, it's a dream come true that Pearl Jam will play in Costa Rica, are you aware of what your fans are going through?
Going to Costa Rica is a dream come true for us too.
This is just our second time in South and Central America and so far it's been great.
I've only been to Costa Rica once and on vacation; it's such a beautiful country and I think we'll be able to stay there for a few days.
So we're excited to bring our music there.
I ask because there's a kind of devotion to the band, the fans live with intensity the days before.
What do they tell their most ardent followers?
Thank you for staying by our side through all these years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica; thank you for waiting so long and we regret that it took us so long to get there.
Some people even refer to his concert as the biggest show of the year.
Does that add a little pressure to your visit?
Some of the biggest shows we've played in the last 21 years happened in the last couple of weeks.
We played a couple of giant shows in Sao Paulo and hopefully that's gotten us in shape for this gig in Costa Rica.
We're really looking forward to playing there.
We love that country, we love surfing and the jungle; for both things, Costa Rica is among the best in the world.
How did you discover Costa Rica and its surfing waves?
We have a lot of friends who are surfers and I have a great friend who lives in Tamarindo and the waves are amazing.
My friends were always going to Costa Rica and Nicaragua, along with Mexico, they're great places to surf, and that's how we found out, from people who love surfing.
Seeing the tour, they've been delivering huge shows with a lot of songs.
What have you got planned for your presentation in Costa Rica?
Since we've never played there before, then we have no restrictions on what we can do.
We're going to try to put on the best show possible with a good variety of songs; we're going to try to play a couple of songs from each album and give our fans a good and diverse repertoire.
You guys never repeat the repertoire.
What's this about?
I think part of it's because we have nine records and we can play over 120 songs and everyone likes different songs, so it's hard to pick which songs to play every night.
When you have two or three songs in your repertoire that you haven't played in a while, it keeps you focused and also keeps you surprised because it reminds you of the reasons why you liked those songs and that you may have forgotten.
That makes the show more interesting for us and therefore I think it also makes it more interesting for people.
With this tour, they're celebrating 20 years.
Looking back, is it hard to believe all they've accomplished?
Yes, I certainly did.
First of all, I think none of us imagined that we'd be in a great rock band and having done it for over 20 years makes it seem like a dream.
We keep counting our blessings and we're so excited that we can keep making music together.
We all love each other and love to make music.
We're lucky to be able to go to places in the world we've always wanted to go.
Things couldn't be better for us.
What did it mean to you to be a key part of the rise of grunge?
It's always been an honor to be part of that group of great bands.
We're very close friends with the people from Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It's amazing when a movement comes from a group of friends and it's something unusual.
Every once in a while, a band from a city comes out, but it's much stranger when five or ten bands come out of the same city at the same time.
We're proud and honored to be part of the Seattle group.
We still play with some of them now and then.
Last year, we were at a festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on their tour, so we're lucky to still be friends with all of them and we're honored to be part of that Seattle sound that came out.
It's also very strange that a band like yours can stay together and with the same members for so long.
Yeah, the four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which, by itself, is a lot longer than most bands last.
First, I think we're all lucky to still be alive, and second, we all care about each other.
We are all very close friends and, thanks to that, musical avenues have also opened up that give everyone the freedom to experiment.
We trust each other with each other's music and it couldn't be better.
Your relationship with the word fame has not been easy, but thanks to your success, you have been able to do whatever you want.
How do they find a balance?
As we've grown, it's been easier to find a balance.
We make sure you don't be too much of a touring act because it's easy to fall into that game of the big crowds and the people who love your music.
As long as you remember that people are there for the music, that reminds you that you should respect the music and what it brought, not get all cranky about being famous and being a rock star, something none of us really care about.
How do you remember your other project Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote some really good songs and at first it was a great thing.
We were a band for almost three years and we never released an album until after Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
There were a lot of frustrations because it lasted this long and the most important thing is that we're still very good friends with Bruce and Greg, who started the band with us and when I hear a song or see a picture I think about the amazing person that Andy was and how he made me laugh, it was always a pleasure to go to work, laugh, talk about music and football and so much more.
He was an amazing human being and we missed him.
The national band Las Robertas will be opening the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know her work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that's why you chose her for the opening?
Yeah, the production sent us videos with several suggestions and that was the band we liked the most, so we're looking forward to seeing what Las Robertas can offer live and it should be very entertaining.
Why do they always change the lyrics to Yellow Ledbetter live?
That's a question for Ed, so I don't know.
He sings it, and I think he sings it with the first thing that comes to his mind.
As a bass player, what are your influences?
There's so many of them.
Among the first ones that come to mind are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C.J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There's so many I could talk all afternoon about the bass players I love.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep grunge relevant even though it's no longer a fad?
I think we all always feel a little disconnected from the word grunge.
When I think about it, it reminds me of the bands I mentioned earlier, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all the other bands that came out at the same time, and, if it's relevant now, I think it's something wonderful because it's music that's worth listening to and bands like Mudhoney are making better music now than ever before.
At first, his music had a darker content and now it has become more positive.
What is the reason for this change?
It's interesting because I think there are a couple of songs on the new album that might seem lighter, but there are also songs, like The End or Just Breathe that qualify as very dark songs even though they can sound a little positive.
With both, when Ed played them to me, I cried when I heard them and they're deeply dark songs.
I think when you grow up and there's some trauma in your life and you lose a family member or a friend, those things start to influence your art and your music and those two songs, they definitely represent that for me.
Also, I think you can be a happy person and still be able to make music that's dark.
