Fujimori is admitted again for medical examination
Former President Alberto Fujimori was admitted to a public hospital on Tuesday to be evaluated for a loss of muscle strength in his legs, his primary care physician said.
Fujimori, 72, who is serving a 25-year prison sentence for human rights violations committed during his rule (1990-2000), suffers from several ailments, including tongue cancer, for which he has undergone four operations and is under control.
Congressman Alejandro Aguinaga, who is his personal physician, told Channel N television that Fujimori will be evaluated for three days at the National Institute of Neoplastic Diseases to determine the reason for the pain and loss of strength in his lower limbs.
Aguinaga commented that in his opinion Fujimori would be a candidate to get the benefit of the pardon for humanitarian reasons, however, he said he does not want it because he knows he is innocent.
He was operated four times for cancer of the tongue, has a weight loss of 18 kilos to which have been added other pathologies such as severe erosive gastritis, pancreatic cyst, kidney stones, hypertension and circulatory problems in the legs, the doctor listed.
Fujimori has been serving his sentence since September 2007 in the National Police Special Operations Directorate.
In April 2009 he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the deaths of 25 people at the hands of an army death squad that operated clandestinely in the first years of his government.
Mujica travels to Mexico to strengthen political ties
An official delegation, led by Uruguayan President José Mujica, and composed of several ministers and businessmen, will begin a visit to Mexico on Tuesday to expand trade between the two nations and address political issues in the region.
Mujica will meet next Wednesday with his Mexican counterpart, Felipe Calderón, the high point of an extensive agenda of meetings with political, commercial authorities and a meeting with the collectivity of Uruguayans living in Mexico, according to the agenda released by the Uruguayan Presidency.
The meeting between the two presidents, in the city of Guadalajara, will be "propitious for the exchange of information on all political matters between the two nations", according to the South American country's presidency on its website.
According to local media, Mujica would seek to get Calderón to support Uruguay in the incident with France that emerged when French President Nicolas Sarkozy included the South American country on a list of tax havens, at the G20 meeting in the French city of Cannes.
In his speech, Sarkozy threatened to exclude from the international community those countries which remain tax havens, a statement which provoked the rejection of Uruguay and the call for consultation of its ambassador in the European country.
Mexico has been chairman of the G20 since November, a group of the world's most powerful emerging and developed countries, and has an agreement with the South American country to exchange tax information to avoid double taxation.
The Uruguay Round of multilateral taxation agreements was concluded in December 1994 and the Uruguay Round of multilateral taxation agreements were signed in December 1995.
In trade, Mexico and Uruguay have a Free Trade Agreement (FTA) in place since 2004, which has increased trade in goods between the two nations.
The mustachioed plumber goes through the three dimensions with "Super Mario 3D Land"
Super Mario has fought tirelessly for 25 years to save Princess Peach from the clutches of the evil Bowser, but never before had he done so in three dimensions: in "Super Mario 3D Land" he will fight for the girl's love in stereoscopic technology.
The title, which hits stores around the world this month, has been designed from the ground up to take advantage of the features of the Nintendo 3DS handheld console, which allows three-dimensional play without the need for glasses.
"Mario is the character who has to say how the stereoscopy without glasses should work", said Nintendo's Spanish press officer Omar Álvarez during the presentation of the video game in Madrid.
Álvarez indicated that "Super Mario 3D Land" is "the first Nintendo video game originally designed for that support", as so far successes like "Star Fox 64 3D" or "Zelda: Ocarine of time 3D" were adaptations of existing titles.
Nintendo's spokesman has maintained that, despite being in 3D, "Super Mario 3D Land" is an "accessible" video game that allows you to enjoy a fast and fluid game.
Alvarez has stated that "Super Mario 3D Land" contains two games in one: the first part is "simple" to hook less skilled users.
Once overcome, the more experienced will be able to give a "second round" to the levels of the game, which this time present greater difficulty.
In addition, users will be able to choose in real time between an "aggressive D" or one that only affects the depth of the action, but it will be necessary to play in three dimensions to be able to overcome the different challenges and "not succumb to optical illusions".
This foray into three-dimensions of Super Mario also means the return of the character to a portable console, a fact that had not been produced since 2005.
In this video game, Nintendo winked at the fans of the series and repeated the formula of the success of previous installments, consisting of the plumber of the mustache having to travel through platforms mined with dangers in order to free Princess Peach.
Although the player will find new moves, environments, costumes and enemies and also a "playable" Luigi.
Colom endorses the extradition of Portillo to the United States
President Álvaro Colom announced on Tuesday that he had given a process for extradition of ex-governor Alfonso Portillo to answer in the United States for conspiracy to launder US$70 million.
Thus ends the process for Guatemala to respond to the request of the northern country that claimed Portillo to be tried there.
In a press conference, Colom said his decision was based on the independence of the judicial and executive powers, taking into account that a sentencing court had already ordered the extradition.
He said that during his term he "did not get his hands on" judicial resolutions and handed over all the extraditions he has seen.
In addition to Portillo, Sergio Ruano Marroquín, for murder and serious injuries, and Edgar Estrada Morales and Victor Estrada Paredes, both for narcotics trafficking, will be extradited.
Colom's actions are an executive procedure after all judicial and constitutional procedures to prosecute the former president from 2000 to 2004 were exhausted.
According to the decisions of the Fifth Criminal Court and the Constitutional Court (CC), Portillo must be extradited once his legal situation in Guatemala is resolved and his human rights are guaranteed.
Portillo was acquitted of embezzling Q120 million from the Ministry of Defense when he was president, which was the process that preceded extradition, but the Public Ministry appealed and reactivated the case.
Trinijove has helped 6,000 at-risk youths
The entity was born to prevent the fall in the marginality of untrained children
The first 25 years of the Trinijove social support institution are important: 6,000 young people at risk of exclusion have been helped to overcome a difficult situation over the course of this quarter century.
In addition, there are over 100 jobs currently being created for this social group.
