Park or mountain?
Architects agree on the opportunity of the call beyond controversies over fees
The municipal competition on the 16 doors reopens the debate on the role of Collserola in Barcelona
In the mid-80s, at the height of the now-defunct Barcelona Metropolitan Corporation (CMB), this Administration printed some promotional posters for Collserola.
The brochure defined the mountain as the great park of metropolitan Barcelona.
In fact, it was accompanied by a comparison, in numbers, to New York's Central Park.
With the death of the CMB, in 1987, the park was again located, in the imagination of many, as the upper limit of Barcelona, being the Catalan capital of the few that are not oriented in the north-south axis but up (mountain) -down (sea).
The classification of Collserola as a nature park is based on this idea.
The reference was no longer Central Park but Yellowstone, with the boars playing the role of Yogi the bear.
In September, the city council called a mega-competition of 16 competitions for as many doors to Collserola.
A doorway is a reference to the idea of a park, no doubt.
Either that or someone's trying to put doors in the field.
The question is: Collserola, park or mountain?
The competition, both for its purely organizational aspect and for what it involves of reflection on the city is the topic of conversation among all Barcelona architects.
It's almost a recurring theme to pick up when two members of this ancient elite cast recognize each other in an elevator.
And this fact leads, precisely, to one of the few coincidences between the views of three Barcelona architects, and university professors, who have come forward.
Miguel Roldán, Daniel Mòdol and Marta Bayona: the competition is timely.
For Roldán, after tackling the coastal front "it becomes necessary" to debate "the mountain front", since the speech of Ildefons Cerdà, the one of the green apples, has not been carried out.
"It is to be assumed that the largest park in Barcelona is the beach.
Among other things, it is very accessible.
Collserola is more complex", says the architect, for whom the title "Collserola's doors" contains a "lexicological trap": they should not be thought of "as accesses to a park, but as the delimitation of areas where action is needed".
Mòdol, like Roldán and Bayona with experience in the urban world, calls the proposal an "intellectual challenge" with "some dangers".
Dangers derived from the "uncertainty that is today projecting the public space" after the experience lived in the 80s and that had in the area of the Forum "his swan song".
The first fear is the very delimitation of boundaries on where to build.
"To limit something is to set the next step", that is, to overstep it.
"We must think of new urban planning instruments, because the current ones [in reference to the Metropolitan General Plan (PGM) ] can lead to real disasters".
More closely adhering to the question, Mòdol believes that, in a simplified way, the Vallès side of Collserola "can be understood as a park, that of Barcelona, no", for a mere topographical question.
Mòdol recalls that there is already a work done by the Patronat of Collserola that "should not fall into a broken sack", although he is grateful for the opportunity that the city offers to his guild to intervene in this project "from the first moment".
And even more, he understands that the proximity of the mountain to the city is the safe passage that allows architects to enter the debate, but "doubt" about whether this technical profile should lead the multidisciplinary teams ("all a hit", he points out) that have had to be created: "The architects should be only a tool".
Bayona insinuates that the answer to the question that gives the title to this piece is complex, because in the basis of the competition there is a lack of a global vision of Collserola: "16 transversal competitions have been called - he says - in the direction of mountain-sea, but there is no longitudinal reading, which sees and understands the area as a whole".
This means that you have chosen to participate in all 16 contests.
Otherwise, a design for one of the doors may clash in program and definition with that of the architect of the door next door.
In his view, yes, the city council should ensure that the strip immediately above the Ronde de Dalt should provide, throughout its length, an area of facilities that would make a smooth transition between the city and the green.
Casino forgives Jonas Larrazábal and he will walk free
After 72 days of rooting, the legal representative of the Casino Red granted the pardon to the brother of the mayor of Monterrey from the process that was followed for alleged blackmail
After 72 days in prison, Manuel Jonás Larrazábal will be released after the legal representative of the Casino Red granted him a pardon before the Second Penal District Court, which is pursuing a process of blackmail against the brother of the mayor of Monterrey.
