Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome gives details of the plane crash that killed Secretary of State Francisco Blake and seven others
The Secretariat of Communications and Transportation (SCT) said the results of the accident that killed the secretary of the Governorate, Francisco Blake Mora, and seven others, indicate that the helicopter impacted directly on the ground in complete structural integrity, without the pilot being able to attempt a forced landing.
During a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, secretary of Communications and Transportation, said that before the aircraft took off, the pilot found that the weather conditions were suitable for flying.
"Elements that appear to indicate the unit had multiple contact with the ground, blades had contact with trees 25 meters away where the unit lost the fuselage".
He also said the unit was designed for 19 people, so it had the necessary requirements to transport personnel.
He also said that in the investigations done in the impact area there is no report of the appearance of pieces on the ground.
"On a search, it is reported that there are no parts or components of the ship elsewhere, the impact occurred structurally.
"The helicopter was designed for 19 passengers, with adequate requirements for transporting passengers.
The terrain has a seven-degree slope at a 30-degree incline.
The Secretary of State said that the priority was to get results as soon as possible, but that the investigation could take several months, even up to a year.
Gilberto López Meyer, director general of Airports and Auxiliary Services, said the helicopter of the Presidential Staff was operating at cruise speed at the time of the impact.
"This information strengthens the hypothesis of a normal cruise operation at the time of impact", he said.
At the press conference, the head of the SCT, Pérez Jácome, listed six relevant elements in the investigation:
Visual flight:
According to the aeronautical regulations the flight was performed under visual flight rules, this implies that the crew must have visibility during the flight and the terrain.
Weather conditions:
Reports from the AICM indicated that conditions were suitable for takeoff, as the aircraft advanced toward the border area between the DF and the State of Mexico, layers of low-lying clouds were present.
Routes selected:
It is likely that the crew sought a lower elevation and better visibility to the Cuernavaca Valley due to the cloudy conditions.
Location of impact.
The impact coordinates and the aircraft's last radar record match, probably before the impact there was no loss of control or alteration in flight path.
Dispersion of aircraft debris in a restricted area:
The information available so far suggests that the impact occurred in a straight, lateral path.
The pattern of dispersal of aircraft debris suggests that the helicopter impacted the ground in structural integrity.
No evidence of fire or explosion was detected:
At the crash site, there is still no evidence in the wreckage of any kind of explosion or fire.
The latest investigation results indicate he may have had multiple contacts with the ground.
During fieldwork, aircraft parts have been found at an elevation of 9,200 feet above mean sea level, the terrain showing a slope ranging from seven degrees to 30 degrees.
The photographs show the sequence in which it was predictably disassembled along this route.
The information provides elements that appear to indicate that the helicopter may have had multiple impacts on the ground.
After a thorough search of a wider area than the cordoned off site, around the crash, no scattered pieces of the aircraft have been found, strengthening the presumption that the impact occurred in conditions of structural integrity.
MSS announces protocol to find gene for obesity
Social Security conducts research to discover the gene for obesity in children and young people; it is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Security (IMSS) announced that it is conducting a research to discover the gene of obesity in children and young people, called protocol 'Genetics of obesity in childhood and adolescence', which will allow to have markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry at the Hospital of Speciality of the National Medical Center Century XXI, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was integrated.
The team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the National Polytechnic Institute's Research and Advanced Studies Center (Cinvestav).
The research is invited to participate in the population whether or not entitled, go to the participating sports units of the IMSS in the Valley of Mexico, where the tests are carried out to minors, every Saturday from 8:00 am.
He stressed that the protocol began in the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (State of Mexico West) and that since October 8, the activity is being carried out in the Nezahualcóyolt Sports Unit (State of Mexico East).
Once the goal of bringing together 500 or 600 minors is met, the study will continue at the Independence Sports Unit (south of the Federal District) and finally at the Morelos Sports Unit (north of the Federal District).
He explained that the purpose of this research is to know the components and importance of genetics with respect to the development of obesity and identify in children and young Mexicans risk factors to prevent the appearance of chronic degenerative diseases.
The aim of the World Diabetes Day, which is being celebrated on 14 November, is to bring together three thousand children and young people aged between six and 14 years, with the consent and supervision of their parents, to apply specific questionnaires on nutrition.
They will also be asked about physical activity and family history of diseases, in order to avoid risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He said that on Saturdays, all participants were given anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist circumference), blood pressure readings, glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin levels and genetic tests (to identify genes associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz López said the investigation was prompted by health professionals' concern about the alarming increase in weight among children.
'Health surveys in 1999 and 2006 showed that in just six years there was a 77 per cent increase in obesity among boys and 47 per cent in obesity among girls; there was also a dramatic rise in overweight', the IMSS specialist said.
He said the justification for the search for markers is based on the fact that the population of the country differs from others by its genetic history.
He reported that on average, the Mexican has 65 percent American Indian, 30 percent European and five percent African heritage and this condition is reflected in genes associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity translate into the inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calories) and which is stored as fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for the participants is the comprehensive assessment of the children, which allows them to detect whether they are overweight or obese.
He even said that there were dark folds (acanthosis) in his neck and forearm, indicating that he may have metabolic changes and even prediabetes.
The information is kept confidential, and the doctors give it in writing to the parents, who are told about each of the measures and lifestyle changes they need to make to prevent disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentary lifestyle, which is the lack of daily physical activity, staying most of the day sitting in front of the television and using means of transportation instead of walking short distances.
It is also due to the high caloric intake, i.e. the greater consumption of sugary drinks, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with high fat and protein content and the genetics that are analyzed in this protocol.
Asphalt from UNAM would prevent potholes
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry of the UNAM, develops asphalt modified with polymers to produce a mixture with better performance, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signals sent by the paving were attended to, it would not be necessary to repair nearly 200 thousand potholes each rainy season in the Metropolitan Zone of the Valley of Mexico, warned Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of the UNAM, who assured that if the process of construction and maintenance of an asphalt paving is adequate, potholes could be reduced in quantity or, even, eliminated completely.
In his lecture A Technological Opinion of Potholes, delivered as part of the International Year of Chemistry, he revealed that his laboratory develops asphalt modified with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to asphalt but with greater mechanical strength, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera estimated that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve its performance and, therefore, the formation of potholes.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, some of high molecular weight, called asphaltens, and others of low molecular weight, called maltenes, which together give the pavement its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of asphalt is that at high temperatures, around 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees Celsius its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees Celsius it presents a nearly solid state, while at very low temperatures, asphalt becomes brittle, he added.
The above means that in the streets the resistance of the asphalt is not uniform, but is changing during the day according to environmental conditions and temperature, warned the specialist in chemical engineering.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered by flexible pavement, which is composed of six layers of materials, of which the last three involve asphalt.
Among the more superficial layers is the asphalt sheath, made up of small stones bathed in asphalt and then compacted.
Each of the pebbles that make up the folder, he said, is covered with asphalt.
As vehicles move and effort is generated, this allows forces to spread very well on the pavement.
If it were modified asphalt, they would spread even better, the chemical engineer said.
Over the asphalt sheath, abundantly, is placed a final layer called a rolling sheath, which is made of a fine stone material, that is, sand that is also bathed in asphalt.
Since it is the layer that will be in contact with the tires of the vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt foil and provide friction on the road.
As the part of the pavement that will receive and spread the effort, the rolling stock also requires proper thickness and care of the material from which it is made.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he said, because it affects the performance of the asphalt foil considerably.
When the soil becomes wet, water diffuses into the inside of the carpet and is difficult to get out, this causes a softening of all layers of the pavement and, therefore, the formation of potholes.
In the process of forming a pothole, he said, the first to wear out is the rolling film and only then is the asphalt foil affected, but the damage does not occur instantly, but is a process that should be addressed at the first signals with adequate maintenance programs.
The National System of Researchers member explained that vehicle load is another important factor in the formation of potholes and, therefore, the thickness of each layer of the pavement should always be in relation to vehicle load and ensure that it is met, to avoid potholes forming frequently.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still much to research and work on asphalt, for example, asphalt emulsions, which in other countries are already even on the market and allow repairing potholes easily and without the need to use high temperatures.
