That was the work of the calligrapher who identified the body of Alfonso Cano.
A lofoscopist from Cali went down in history as the man who confirmed the death of "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these officials is key.
On November 4, a lofoscopist from the Cali CTI went down in history as the man who confirmed the identity of the FARC's top leader: "Alfonso Cano", through the cotejo of his fingerprints.
Of the seven lofoscopists who work in the CTI section, that week Eliazar González, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been working in the area of judicial investigation for 21 years, was on the "availability" shift.
At the beginning of his career, González worked in Chocó municipalities, where he often had to go into the jungle for more than five days to get to the place where the bodies were to be identified.
In 2000 he moved to the capital of the Valley and, after completing the corresponding courses, he specialized in lofoscopy, which is the study of friction skin, that is, the palms of the hands and feet.
The week of the operation against alias Alfonso Cano Eliazar was warned to wear minimum clothing for three days.
Something big was waiting for him.
On Friday night he left for Cauca in a helicopter from Palmyra.
He knew he had to identify two corpses and that one of them was suspected to be that of the man who led the world's oldest guerrilla, so he was asked to carry the decadactilar card of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name).
However, when he arrived with the search team at the site of the body, he did not recognize it because of its physical appearance, which was very different from what he had seen in the media.
He was beardless, dressed like a local peasant, no glasses and much thinner.
But the prints don't lie.
Accompanied by a Galtonian magnifying glass, ink, a transplant and a flashlight, Eliazar compared the fingerprints from the corpse with those on the card.
His eye didn't miss: it was "Alfonso Cano".
That night, the man from Puerto Tejada was in charge of confirming to the Minister of Defense, Juan Carlos Pinzón, that he was the top FARC chief.
Searching for the print
For a Sijín of Cali dactiloscopist the recognition made by President Juan Manuel Santos to Eliazar González, in the press conference for the operation against "Cano", is very significant.
A lot of people don't know our work.
Dactyloscopy is an exact science, with no margin for error, that can be key in solving crimes.
In addition to identifying corpses, lofoscopists support investigations into crimes such as theft and murder and confirm the identity of people caught.
When caught, many criminals present false IDs or no papers.
We take their fingerprints and run them through the database.
The investigator related that in one case of theft, he had to remove a piece of a wall from a house, because the thief had leaned his hand on that place to pull out a safe full of jewelry and money.
"The walls are difficult because they are not proper surfaces to take a fingerprint, but in that case we could get the fingerprint of the entire hand and identify the delinquent, who had participated in different thefts", he recalled.
Fingerprints can also rule out or reinforce suspects in homicide cases.
A man was found dead recently, liquor bottles all around him.
The investigation determined that a family member could be a suspect in the crime and indeed a print on the bottle matched.
Although this doesn't guarantee that he was the killer, it does place him at the scene of the crime.
A typist at the ITC explained that on objects "fingerprints are taken with chemical or physical reagents".
When they appear, a graft or tape is used to lift them.
After this, the prints are sent to the Asif, which is the criminal database, or the Registry.
"The problem is that there are still many undocumented Colombians", the CTI expert said.
He clarified that not everything is as shown on the television show CSI.
Just as not everything that glitters is gold, not everything you touch becomes a footprint.
However, if it can be used, if the respective co-ordination is carried out.
