Japan reborn after earthquake
GDP grows by 1.5% thanks to domestic consumption and ends the downward spiral that began in March
Since March last year, the Japanese economy has been paralysed, still recovering from the devastating earthquake that turned into a nuclear crisis, the worst catastrophe the country has suffered since World War II.
Initial estimates by the Tokyo government put the material losses at $300 billion, a blow that, despite the difficult global context, seems to have subsided.
After three consecutive quarters of declines, the Gross Domestic Product data for July and September turned the page, definitely: GDP increased by 1.5% compared with the previous quarter and by 6% in annualized terms.
The second quarter - for the Japanese, the fiscal year starts in March 2012 - also represents the highest growth rate since January to March 2010.
The recovery is partly explained by the uptick in the purchase of machinery for restoring areas devastated by the earthquake and subsequent tsunami.
Indeed, firms increased their investments by 1.1%, compared with the 0.9% decrease in capital expenditure observed from January to March, the first decrease after six months of uninterrupted increases.
The real upturn in the Japanese economy, however, is not solely based on the Keynesian drive to use crises to strengthen - or rebuild - infrastructure, to use the shortages to grow from scratch.
Japan has reawakened, largely thanks to the evolution of domestic consumption, which now accounts for 60% of Japanese GDP.
This variable climbed by 1%, driven by increased expenditure on vehicles, travel and leisure activities.
The Stigma of the Yen
Tokyo has committed itself to the domestic market, when the yen - the Japanese currency - has become one of the "safe havens" chosen by investors fleeing the eurozone debt crisis and the gloomy US outlook, a privilege that weighs heavily on the accounts of exporting companies.
With a stronger currency, products are more expensive abroad, a serious setback for a country whose economic buoyancy is determined by the health of big tech groups.
