An expert committee says euthanasia and assisted suicide should be legalized
Canadians live in denial of death, says report from Royal Society of Canada
In the field of palliative care, the Committee calls for governments, healthcare institutions and doctors to work together to ensure the best palliative care, not just for cancer.
Canadian society lives in denial of death.
In fact, only 9% of Canadians are willing to talk to their doctor about the conditions in which they want to die and make arrangements to do so.
This is one of the conclusions of a major report by the Royal Society of Canada, which included six experts from various fields, including ethics, law, and medicine.
This committee recommends that the Government amend the Penal Code to allow assisted suicide and euthanasia when the patient is faced with such an option and has been judged competent to make the decision.
To begin, the experts cite a recent survey by the Economist Intelligence Unit that compared the quality of death in 40 countries around the world.
Although Canada ranks tenth, the study notes that "the medicalization of death in Canada has created a culture in which people are afraid to talk about death".
With or without medication, 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, according to experts selected by the Royal Society of Canada.
And, even though most Canadians wish to die at home, 68.6 percent of them end up dying in a hospital.
Overall, the highest rate in this respect is recorded in Quebec, where 86% of deaths occur in hospitals.
On the sensitive issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the report's authors reached conclusions that do not coincide with the position of the Federal Government, which has already stated that it does not wish to amend the Penal Code in relation to euthanasia and assisted suicide.
However, according to the experts, who have also studied the situation in all countries where such practices have been legalized or are not a criminal offence, there is no evidence that the fact that they are not considered a criminal offence has not led to abuse of their application, i.e. the use of euthanasia or assisted suicide with persons who are not competent or who have not given their consent.
The report's co-author, Jocelyn Downie, said yesterday via teleconference that, on the contrary, more excesses were observed in countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide had not been legalized.
"Euthanasia is practiced in Canada, although it is clearly illegal".
"Assisted suicide is practiced in Canada, although it is clearly illegal", explains Jocelyn Downie.
Canadians in favor of euthanasia
Recall that 85% of Canadians have already spoken in favor of euthanasia, believing that it would allow people who are about to die to alleviate their suffering, according to a 2010 Angus Reid poll.
In addition, 66% believe that legalizing euthanasia will not imply that the lives of elderly or disabled people are of less value.
As for people who have practiced assisted suicide, 41% of those surveyed believe that no proceedings should be initiated against them.
The situation with regard to the maintenance or interruption of health care for a patient is not so clear, the report authors say.
In addition, among its recommendations, it suggests that it be stated in the Penal Code that the withdrawal of healthcare, if legally refused, is not a criminal offence.
The Committee of Experts also calls for training of health professionals in the duty to respect the fact that a patient can refuse care at the end of his life without fear of being sued.
In the field of palliative care, the Committee calls for governments, healthcare institutions and doctors to work together to ensure the best palliative care, not just for cancer.
Finally, with regard to palliative or terminal sedation, which is already widely used in Canadian healthcare institutions, the Committee calls for it to be considered as euthanasia and subjected to the same procedures, unless it is used to reduce physical pain.
Other experts have reservations
Other experts in the field of health law have already expressed reservations about the conclusions of the report of the Royal Society of Canada.
Pierre Deschamps, a specialist in health law, called the position of the experts signing the report "extreme", not least because euthanasia is not limited to terminally ill patients.
"This leaves the door open to a situation where someone who is tired of living and is over 18 can ask for help to commit suicide", says Deschamps, who yesterday consulted a summary of the report.
Mr Deschamps also stresses that the report's authors seem to prioritise personal autonomy over any other value in society.
But he adds that "in society, there are labels and limitations".
Health Law specialist Margaret Somerville also expressed her "strong opposition" to the report's conclusions, which she called "manifestly pro-euthanasia".
Margaret Somerville, also of the Royal Society of Canada, especially questions the lack of abuse in certain countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are legal, such as the Netherlands and Oregon.
