Two days after the Arab League suspended Syria, the European Union has tightened sanctions on Damascus, while Turkey and Jordan, Syria's neighbours, have spoken out in favour of President Assad's abdication.
King Abdullah II of Jordan was yesterday the first Arab leader to ask President Bashar al-Assad to "leave power" in Syria, where some 40 civilians and members of the regime's forces have already died.
"If Bashar really cares about his country, he should resign, as well as create the conditions for a new phase of Syrian political life", the king of Jordan, Syria's neighbor, said in an interview with the BBC.
The Turkish Foreign Minister, Ahmet Davutoglu, said he regretted that Turkey's mediation efforts with the Syrian regime since the beginning of the year had failed.
"Those who are not at peace in the Middle East with their peoples and cannot satisfy them will leave", he declared, referring to Syria, a neighbouring country with which Turkey is taking an increasingly tough stance.
The United States, for its part, welcomed the Arab League and European Union's decisions to "strengthen the consensus against Assad and the actions of the Syrian regime".
"The international community, the United States, the EU, the Arab League and other countries, such as Turkey, are taking an increasingly tough line" on the crackdown in Syria, says State Department spokesman Mark Toner.
Meanwhile, 16 civilians and at least 19 members of the regime forces have already lost their lives in the Deraa region of southern Syria, the Syrian Observatory for Human Rights (OSDH) has announced.
Two other civilians have died "during heavy shelling and machine gun fire in Jobar" in the besieged city of Homs, the NGO said.
During a press conference, Syrian Foreign Minister Walid Al Mualem said the country was "moving towards the end of the crisis".
The European Union has also reacted strongly to the Arab League's decision to suspend its functions in Damascus, which it considers a 'dangerous step'.
Syria "will not falter", he added, guaranteeing that "the plots plotted against Syria will fail".
Following the decision to suspend Syria, the Arab League is currently studying a "civilian protection mechanism" and wants to send 500 members of Arab human rights organizations, media and military observers to the country.
