The Commission
Monti asks time for markets and sacrifices for Italians
The future head of the Italian government, Mario Monti, has asked for some time for the markets to form their team and launch a programme that will include "sacrifices" aimed at regaining the credibility lost during the last months of the Berlusconi government.
The former European Commissioner debated yesterday with the political parties and today he met with the trade unions and employers.
He should form a relatively small cabinet, made up of technocrats outside Parliament.
'Monti has spoken of a broad programme with many sacrifices,' said Francesco Nucara, a member of one of the many small parliamentary groups taking part in the meetings, after meeting the appointed President of the Council.
The President of the Chamber of Deputies, Gianfranco Fini, said he hoped that Mario Monti would ask for a vote of confidence in Parliament before Friday to ensure that the new Government had sufficient support.
The consultations will end with the presentation by Mr Monti of a limited list of no doubt a dozen Ministers to the Head of State, Mr Giorgio Napolitano.
Monti commented on the nervousness of the stock markets and bondholders yesterday, asking for time.
In "democracy, there are precise time limits" for forming a Government and preparing its programme, he stressed, adding that he is "confident that the markets will have patience and will understand".
His appointment as President initially won the approval of the markets, but then there was concern, particularly after an unexpected fall in industrial production in the euro area in September.
The Prime Minister-designate should create a team mainly made up of technocrats, even if he has stressed that he would like to include "politicians".
The new government must operate until 2013, the date of the next legislative, he considers.
According to the President of the Chamber of Deputies, Gianfranco Fini, the new Government will get the vote of confidence from Parliament before Friday.
The Commission has also adopted a proposal for a directive on the protection of workers from the risks related to exposure to ionising radiation.
A spokesman for European Commissioner Olli Rehn stressed that 'even with a new government, our diagnosis of the Italian economy will not change'.
The EU, convinced that Rome will not achieve its goal of achieving budgetary balance in 2013 despite austerity plans adopted in recent months, has called for further stringent measures.
The European Parliament has also adopted a resolution on the situation in the former Yugoslavia, which calls for the EU to take a more active role in the fight against terrorism.
Monti, famous for his competence and independence as European Commissioner (1994-2004), represents a "change of epoch" for Italy after 17 years of "Berlusconiism"; the "professor" symbolizes "the challenge of seriousness" and "another Italy", the editors claim.
The big unknown will be the longevity of your team.
President Napolitano wants to avoid early elections, as Italy has to place some 200 billion euros in government bonds before April 2012.
A Russian scientist has collaborated with Iran's nuclear program.
A Russian scientist, Vycheslav Danilenko, has collaborated with Iran in developing a detonator that can be used with a nuclear weapon, an American NGO specializing in atomic risk said on Monday.
In identifying the investigator, the Institute for Science and International Security (ISIS) relies on a recent report by the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) and other documents issued by that UN agency.
The IAEA expressed its "grave concern" last week about a "possible military dimension" of Iran's nuclear programme.
According to ISIS, based extensively on IAEA documents, Danilenko, born in 1934, would have worked for three decades, since the 1960s, at a Soviet military nuclear center in Chelyabinsk (Ural) and would have been involved in the manufacture of synthetic explosion diamonds.
In 1989 or 1991, he would have left the centre to form a company focused on the production of "nanodiamonds" in Kiev.
The economic problems of his company led him to contact the Iranian Embassy in Ukraine in 1995.
He is believed to have cooperated with the Iranian programme between 1996 and 2002, before returning to Russia.
In its latest report, the IAEA mentions that there are "clear indications that Iran is developing" a nuclear detonation system "with the help of a foreign expert who not only knew the technique well but also, as one member state has reported to the Agency, worked for most of his career on such technology in his home country's military nuclear program".
Crimes and crimes against Muslims have increased by 50%
Crimes and crimes against Muslims have increased by nearly 50 percent between 2009 and 2010, while, over the same period, other types of racial and religious violence have declined or increased only slightly, according to statistics released by the FBI on Monday.
According to these figures, the total number of acts of violence against Muslims has increased from 107 in 2009 to 160 in 2010, i.e. by 49%, compared with a 13% increase in acts of violence against Catholics, a 4% reduction in crimes against Jews and an overall 14% increase in anti-religious crimes and offences.
The total number of "hate crimes" has risen slightly to 6,628, of which 47.3 percent are due to racial differences and 20 percent to religious differences, according to the FBI.
"After a decline in 2009, it is worrying that such crimes have re-emerged", Human Rights First said. "The increase in acts of violence against Muslims is particularly significant", the organization said in a statement.
"Human Rights First has long argued that violence against Muslims, as well as all types of hate crimes, should be considered a serious violation of human rights", adds Paul Legendre, a senior human rights official.
"The U.S. government can and should work to end such abuses", he adds, noting that such efforts could include improving police reporting on "hate crimes".
The "hate crime" in U.S. federal law was inherited from the civil rights era.
This legislation was passed after the death of Martin Luther King to punish acts of violence based on race, color, religion, origin and now sexual orientation.
Twitter changes its platform and looks more like Facebook
The microblogging site Twitter modified the presentation of its platform on Monday to allow its users, in particular, to observe the activity of the people they follow, which causes its service to look a little more like Facebook.
A new tab "activity" and another called "name" allow you to more legibly and live follow the activity of other "Twittos", that is, those Internet users whose messages ("tweets") you follow on the Internet or who follow you.
This lets you know if they follow up on messages, subscribe to new accounts, rate a message as a favorite, etc.
The new Twitter formula was tested "with a small percentage of users in August" before being rolled out to the rest of the network on Monday, Twitter spokeswoman Carolyn Penner told AFP.
Twitter, which was known for its uninstinctive operation, with slightly esoteric terms (RT to forward a message from another person, followfriday pour recommander de suivre un autre utilisateur) faisant le bonheur des initiés, s'ouvre ainsi à un public plus large avec un maniement plus comparable à celui des réseaux grand public Facebook et Google+.
On the network, users have been debating the interest of this innovation through "tweets" with different opinions.
"It's useless, it's invasive and it looks too much like Facebook", writes @jemb123.
"The Activity feature is going to help me better follow some elements of my Twitter feed", writes @dannykronstrom.
Austria
Introduction of a budgetary 'golden rule' in the Constitution
The ruling Social Democratic/Christian Democrat grand coalition government in Austria decided on Tuesday to include in the constitution a budgetary "golden rule" to reduce the public deficit and thus avoid a possible downgrade of Austria's sovereign rating by credit rating agencies (triple A).
It was the Socialist Chancellor, Werner Faymann, who announced this decision after a Council of Ministers meeting, when the Austrian public debt is 74.6%, well above the 60% ceiling set by the Maastricht Treaty, but clearly below the debts of countries such as Italy, Greece and Spain.
"If Austria's solvency were reduced by a single level, from AAA to AA+, we would have to pay an extra EUR 3 billion in interest each year", said Christian Democrat Vice-Chancellor for Foreign Affairs Michael Spindelegger.
Austria is thus responding to a request from the Brussels summit of 26 October to the euro area Member States, in which the Heads of State or Government called for the reduction of the public deficit and the restoration of the balance of public accounts to be included in the Constitution or in a law of equivalent value before the end of 2012.
The Austrian Government's approach is similar to the 'German model', as Germany was the first European country to adopt such a 'rule'.
By 2017, the structural government deficit should decrease each year by 0,75% of gross domestic product (GDP) and, from 2017, the federal government structural deficit should not exceed 0,35% of GDP each year, while the regional states, as well as the municipalities, should present balanced budgets.
The objective is to reduce public debt to the 60% criterion set by the Maastricht Treaty by 2020/2021.
A strong yen
No threat of further foreign exchange intervention
Japanese Prime Minister Yoshihiko Noda warned on Tuesday that Japanese authorities would re-intervene in the currency mark-up if the yen continued to rise.
"We will intervene, as we did last time, if we find that there is excessive volatility" in the yen exchange rate, Noda told the Senate.
On Tuesday, the yen rose to near historic highs brought on by the Japanese authorities' intervention on October 31.
On that day, Tokyo sold off massive yen for dollars to bring down the value of the Japanese currency, which had just hit a new record since 1945 against the U.S. currency.
But the yen has been steadily rising since then, driven by purchases by investors who see it as a "safe haven" in these uncertain times of global economic slowdown and a debt crisis in Europe.
The dollar has fallen below 77 yen and the euro has fallen below the symbolic bar of 105 yen, reaching levels close to those caused by the latest intervention.
Before the 2008-2009 financial crisis, the dollar was trading at around 120 yen and the euro at over 160 yen.
This explosion in the Japanese currency is hurting the archipelago's exports, since it makes Made in Japan products more expensive and reduces the value of the income generated abroad by Japanese companies when they convert it into the national currency.
"Japan is struggling to rebuild" after the March 11 earthquake and tsunami that devastated the Tohoku region (northeast), Noda said, fearing that the rise in the yen will cut the weak recovery.
The world's third largest economy has recovered in the third quarter (by 1.5% on the previous quarter) for the first time in a year, thanks to an increase in exports and consumption by households affected by the disaster.
But the Prime Minister felt that the high yen level did not reflect "Japan's economic foundations".
Finance Minister Jun Azumi has asked the Bank of Japan (BoJ), which opened a two-day meeting of its Monetary Policy Council on Tuesday, to take all possible measures to weaken the yen.
However, the institution's Deputy Governor, Hirohide Yamaguchi, warned that the BoJ had already taken "appropriate measures", implying that no further monetary flexibility should be expected on Wednesday.
During its last meeting in late October, the issuer increased its purchases of Treasury bills by five trillion yen (€47 billion), bringing the threshold for funds for the acquisition of various financial securities to 55 trillion yen (€519 billion) to flood the liquidity market.
The euro area:
The guys grow, the bags weaken.
The risk of contagion from the debt crisis continues to weigh on European indices.
Despite the appointment of new Heads of Government in Greece and Italy, and improved growth in France and Germany, rates in the weaker countries continue to rise.
Still concerned about the stability of the stability of the euro area, European stock markets sink a little further into the negative zone on Tuesday 15 November.
In Paris, at 10 o'clock, the CAC 40 loses 1.4% and stands at 3.064 points.
The Dax loses 0.4% in Frankfurt and 0.1% in London.
"In light of the new tensions in relation to loan yields in the most affected euro area countries, stock markets worldwide continue to reap some of their recent gains".
