The Tokyo Stock Exchange closed down 0.7%, renewing market participants' concerns about Europe's ability to contain the debt crisis.
"Japan, like the rest of the world, is looking to Europe and trade will continue to be conducted within a narrow range of variation, so investors will have no evidence that the situation has stabilised", said Mitsushige Akino, fund manager at Ichiyoshi Investment Management.
The re-emergence of concerns about the future of the euro area is affecting the single currency, which continued to fall on Tuesday.
The euro remains at its lowest level in a month and a half.
By 10 a.m., the European currency was worth $1,3570, a drop of 0.4%.
According to traders, it has lost value after Chancellor Angela Merkel's CDU party, which met on Monday in Congress, adopted a motion that provides, in particular, for the option for a struggling country to leave the eurozone without leaving the European Union.
Italian and Spanish rates exceed 6%
The credit rates in Italy and Spain remain at very worrying levels.
On Tuesday morning, the yield on Italian 10-year bonds was 6.85%, while Spanish bonds at the same maturity were 6.2%.
These tensions over interest rates in the southern countries, but also in France, continue to fuel the fears of the interveners.
The head of the future Italian government, Mario Monti, has asked the markets for time to improve the situation in Italy, which risks suffocating under the weight of its debt.
The new Greek Prime Minister, Lucas Papademos, said that implementing the decisions taken at the euro area summit on 27 October would be the "main task" of his government.
Spain is in the crosshairs of the markets, while on Sunday the legislative elections will be held there.
The spread between 10-year bonds in Germany and Spain has reached a new all-time high.
Waiting for euro area growth figures
Statistically, France recorded economic growth of 0.4% in the third quarter, a more favourable figure than the 0.3% forecast, driven by domestic consumption.
The Insee, however, revised down the second-quarter figure, with a 0.1% reduction in gross domestic product (GDP) rather than a stagnation.
Besides, the fourth quarter is what really worries economists.
Germany, on the other hand, recorded growth of 0.5% over the same period.
The first forecasts for the euro area as a whole are expected at 11 a.m. after the European Commission warned of the risk of a new recession.
Energy policy:
Facts must prevail over dogma.
If there is one issue that cannot be dealt with by considering short-term considerations or simply by thinking about emotions, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly influence the purchasing power and competitiveness of enterprises.
It is fitting that an election meeting should be the time to reflect on these issues and on the place of nuclear energy.
The debate will only be useful if it considers the economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, on rational data.
Now that we have seven billion people on the planet, the demographic evolution will mean that the demand for electricity will double by 2050, unless a huge part of the world's population is deprived of a vital element.
At the same time, the growing scarcity of fossil resources must be addressed in order to continue to produce electricity continuously, without forgetting the urgent need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to combat climate change, a topic that has disappeared from the ecological debate.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these parameters.
Germany is therefore alone in its decision to abandon nuclear energy.
This is not the case in Belgium, which is subject to the need to find a source capable of replacing it, or in Switzerland, which is only concerned with building the latest generation of power stations.
On the other hand, Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to name a few, are moving ahead with their projects.
The United States, for its part, after Fukushima decided to add a unit to its park, resuming the construction of a power plant interrupted after the Three Mile Island accident.
The German model of renewable energy is sometimes cited as an example, but the reality is quite different.
The choice of Berlin will mean higher electricity prices, greater energy dependence on increased imported gas, particularly from Russia, and increased CO2 emissions from the construction of gas and coal-fired power stations.
In a few months, the damaging effects will be felt.
The case of Denmark is worth considering.
Europe's champion in the wind sector, which generates 30% of its electricity, is also a major user of coal and gas because of the intermittency of the wind.
On the contrary, thanks to the consistency of our energy policy, our neighbours pay a 40% higher electricity bill than French households.
While in a globalised economy the cost of energy is a key factor in competitiveness and a guarantee of maintaining industrial utility in the national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
For that reason, any significant reduction in nuclear energy would mean a sharp rise in the price of electricity, which would undermine the realism of the wonderful statements about reindustrialising our country and defending our purchasing power.
This is a price that the vast majority of French people refuse to pay and are not in fact opposed to this type of energy in principle, according to surveys.
We must remember that the energy policy of our country has failed to build an industrial sector with 125,000 direct jobs and 410,000 indirect jobs.
Export-oriented in scope, it encompasses a galaxy of SMEs specialised in international markets and capable of creating jobs that cannot be relocated.
If France were to abandon nuclear energy, it would mean the sacrifice of a large part of these SMEs and the loss of 6 billion euros a year in French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
What electrician would order an EPR designed to run for 60 years when its manufacturer is scheduled to collapse?
To solve the equation of nuclear energy, we must admit that there is no miraculous source of electricity production, just as there is no diabolical source.
The Commission notes that the Commission has not yet decided whether the aid is compatible with the internal market.
In the case of nuclear energy, it is essential to maintain the highest level of safety.
In France we have a safety authority which exercises strict and transparent control over both the existing power stations and the construction of Flamanville.
Our teams, with their recognized professionalism, are also obsessed with safety.
In the last half century, the nuclear sector has suffered three serious accidents.
Only one, the Three Mile Island accident, occurred under normal operating conditions; it caused no consequences to people or the environment.
In Chernobyl, the accident was due to reactor design and unforgivable human error.
In Fukushima, some people seem to forget that the accident was caused by two natural disasters of unprecedented magnitude, which killed tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will learn from this accident, as it did from the two previous ones.
Thanks to these developments and cooperation between safety authorities and French and German operators and manufacturers, the EPR is designed to withstand such phenomena.
While all the electricity players who wish to build a power station are studying it, the interruption of its construction in Flamanville would be a great gift to Areva's and EDF's competitors, since it would leave them free to assume leadership in the inevitable development of the nuclear sector.
It is essential and legitimate to seek the best energy options for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let emotion, dogma and partisan maneuvering dominate a debate so important for the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Immigration - A Burden or an Opportunity for the Economy?
The immigration policy of Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticised from various points of view: the saturation of the police, judicial and administrative services subject to the policy of figures, the compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of France as a 'country of human rights'.
More recently, it is the administrative harassment of foreign students that has made headlines, with the Interior Minister (see Libération newspaper of 23 May) proclaiming recently that France "does not need foreign talent, workers or waiters".
However, it is rarely analysed from an economic point of view.
The point is that there is a fair amount of consensus on this issue between the left and the right.
On the right, Jacques Chirac set the tone by declaring in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed should not be a problem for a country with nearly two million migrant workers", while on the left, Michel Rocard set the tone by explaining that France "cannot take on all the misery in the world" in 1990.
The only difference, the degree of generosity
In 2005, both the left and the right shared the fear of the invasion of national territory by a mob of Polish plumbers.
Both sides consider immigrants to be a burden on the French economy and society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity with which they act toward immigrants.
In his programme, François Hollande merely includes trivia, saying that co-development will solve the 'migration problem'.
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may be electorally lucrative, but economically it's very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out in a recent book summarizing the latest knowledge on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is broad consensus among experts on the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages and employment in host countries.
The limitation of immigration weakens growth and harms employment.
Fears about the impact of immigrants are based on the idea that they can replace domestic workers, particularly low-skilled ones, by pressuring them to reduce their wages.
But experience shows that in reality immigrants are complementary rather than substitute for national workers and mainly work in sectors where there is a lack of employment.
Low skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract national workers and the most skilled in dynamic sectors where training does not meet the demand for staff.
A positive effect on wages
Just as a surgeon would have difficulty working in a country where there is a shortage of anaesthetists, the complementarity between nationals and immigrants causes the arrival of the latter to have a positive influence on the salaries and employment of nationals.
In view of the above, Giovanni Peri calculated that a 1% increase in migration flows would lead to a long-term increase in real wages of between 0.6% and 0.9%.
And, without taking into account the fact that the diversity that immigrants bring contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (there is a large proportion of naturalized American Nobel laureates and companies like Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Immigrants are also net contributors to social systems, contributing on average 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The International Labour Organisation estimates, for example, that in Germany an immigrant who arrives at the age of 30 will make a net contribution (income less expenses) of 150,000 euros to the public budget on average over his lifetime.
At the beginning of his term, Nicolas Sarkozy wanted to go looking for the growth points he was missing "with his teeth".
These teeth, which deterred immigrants, had exactly the opposite effect.
Europe invented democracy, it just needs to think about a European democracy
Democracy is a precious good, but it is also fragile.
The European continent should be able to remember this because, although it was invented in Athens over two thousand years ago, throughout the 20th century it has suffered the tragedies of the World War, totalitarianism, the Holocaust, the gulag, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal, the colonels in Greece.
Some may have thought that for democracy to triumph definitively over its enemies, it would be enough to exercise the vote as directly as possible.
We know, since Napoleon the Little, that this was a thoughtful thing.
Universal suffrage, although a necessary condition for democracy, is not sufficient in itself and can even become an 'instrument of oppression', as the republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot once said.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, an organization, a separation and control of powers, an education, Lights, economic and social solidarity, justice.
The crisis we are experiencing in Europe is an economic crisis, but it is about to become a political and democratic crisis.
The palinody of the true-false Greek referendum had a twofold revealing effect in this respect: it showed the need for a powerful return to the political sphere, but also the worrying sense of its impossibility, of its incongruity.
This ambivalence must be reflected on in order to overcome it.
The truth is that the front lines of the democratic battle have now shifted and that, in many cases, the Republican soldiers are no longer advancing in the right direction.
We will not win if we demand a succession of national referendums, organised according to needs and in a disorderly manner.
A blank signature to the absolute European monarch or a blank check to the nationalist hole: what options for the citizen!
No, we do not want to make a coup, but a common, full-fledged, calm and continuous exercise of choice and democracy, this time at European level.
There is no crisis in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal (in fact, we wouldn't know where to end the list), because there is only one crisis, the crisis of Europe.
The whole of Europe is the one that is subject to the orders of the markets and the rating agencies, the one that suffers from their impotence and lack of solidarity.
It is Europe as a whole that is being humiliated on the international scene.
We are concerned about the transfer of sovereignty to Europe, but it is all of Europe that is slowly losing sovereignty and with it each of its nations.
The most urgent thing is that popular sovereignty should take back the helm of the European project.
Because only together can Europeans reduce their debt burden, free themselves from markets and prepare for their future through investment.
The way out of the crisis will require decisions at European level which cannot be taken without full democratic legitimacy, unless they lead to disaster.
After a long struggle against this proposal by the Socialists and Jacques Delors, everyone is now calling for European economic governance.
Let it be.
But to think of it without greater political and democratic integration, and without it being lived as such by the citizens, would be another madness and would lead us to a new deadlock.
We must take up a new stage in European construction.
To build the Republic in France, it was necessary to "make" republicans.
A revolution motivated by interests would not be enough.
This lesson is still applicable.
We must build a more economically integrated Europe.
This can only be achieved by building a more democratic Europe at the political level, a true European people's sovereignty.
To build Europe, we must make Europeans.
Contactless cards are becoming more common
The world chip card fair opens on Tuesday in Villepinte, near Paris, with an upbeat atmosphere.
In fact, 2011 should end with an 11% increase in global sales of micro-processor cards (bank cards, SIM phones, etc.), totalling 6 billion units, according to calculations by the Eurosmart office.
The most powerful segment is contactless technology, which allows you to pay for public transport or shopping simply by bringing the card to a reader.
This year, 460 million contactless chip cards will be sold worldwide, 320 million more than the year before!
Its share should continue to increase in 2012 (expected 580 million units) and represent about 10% of the global chip card market (6,925 million cards).
Europe, which has long lagged behind the Asia-Pacific region, is gaining ground in the contactless payment sector.
Approximately 26 million Visa bank cards already have this feature, which is accepted at 75,000 payment terminals.
In France, the start is more modest: 400,000 contactless Visa cards are in use.
But the big surfaces work for four.
Carrefour has issued 2.5 million contactless Pass MasterCard cards this year.
To get the upper hand, however, banks need to make them available to their customers.
"Two major French banks have committed to systematically extending contactless banking cards to their customers in the future", says Gérard Nébouy, CEO of Visa Europe France.
Banks are testing mobile phone payments
But it is only a first step towards the payment method of the future: the mobile phone.
At present, there are few devices equipped with Near Field Communication (NFC) technology, which is essential for making transactions.
"They're falling behind".
"But it should finally experience a real boom next year".
"We expect to sell between 80 and 120 million units worldwide in 2012", explains Marc Bertin, president of Eurosmart.
But the banks are taking the lead.
The Crédit agricole bank announced yesterday the launch of a test between December and next June in Caen.
The iPhones of about 200 customers and collaborators will be equipped with a case that allows contactless payment.
The BPCE has a similar project in Strasbourg and Marseille.
And the Société générale also said yesterday that it is preparing to market an offer that will allow its customers to pay contactlessly via their mobile.
From the Sahara to Nigeria, the terrorist front is on the rise
Paris is concerned about the links between Al Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb and the Boko Haram sect.
The long-held suspicions of links between the terrorist group Al Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb (Aqmi) and the Nigerian sect of Boko Haram have been confirmed.
On Sunday, the Algerian Deputy Foreign Minister, Abdelkader Messahel, even claimed that Algiers already "has the certainty".
"The way both organizations operate and the intelligence reports show that they are cooperating", he explained, without providing further details.
Paris seems to have come to a similar conclusion.
The investigation into the kidnapping of two Frenchmen in Niger last January would have restarted the catwalks.
Abducted from a restaurant in Niamey by people linked to Aqmi, Antoine de Léocour and Vincent Delory died the next day along with several of their captors during an operation launched by French special forces.
In the rubble of the raid, French and Nigerian investigators discovered several phone chips that belonged to the terrorists.
The terrorist axis
The study of the calls made points to several interlocutors based in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), two numbers have particularly caught the attention of investigators: one leads to a Nigerian who has been in Maiduguri, a city in northern Nigeria, the birthplace of Boko Haram, for a long time, and the other to a man who is allegedly close to Aqmi and the sect.
"This is progress, but we certainly must wait to possess more formal evidence before talking about operational cooperation between Aqmi and Boko Haram".
"But it is possible".
"We have known for years that the sect enjoys outside financial and intellectual support and is becoming more active", says Kunle Amuwo, a Nigerian researcher.
In recent months, such 'supports' have become increasingly evident in Boko Haram's evolution and rhetoric or in its modes of operation, which now involve the use of increasingly complex kamikazes or explosive devices similar in style to those used by Aqmi.
The international community, starting with Washington, has since been pressuring Abuja to take into account the problems generated by Boko Haram.
Nigerian authorities, in fact, have long considered the group as a community of enlightened people of little interest.
A quick success
Founded in 2002 in Maiduguri around a mosque, a school and the fundamentalist imam Mohammed Yusuf, Boko Haram (which means, in Hausa, "Western education is a sin"), incites the establishment of an Islamic emirate in the Muslim north of Nigeria.
In this poor region, the association is experiencing rapid success.
It is politicized and demands strict respect for sharia law, while its militants launch into the fight against the ungodly central government.
The latter are primarily aimed at churches, bars, administration.
