Nord Stream, new gateway for Russian gas to Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which links Western Europe directly to Russia via the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has already been put into operation.
It must supply gas to meet the needs of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with great pomp.
Last Tuesday, more than 500 guests, including four Heads of State and Government, took part on the shores of the Baltic Sea, amid orchestral music and a delicate buffet, in the inauguration of Nord Stream, the new gas pipeline that directly links Russia with Germany under the sea.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and their Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte have together turned the steering wheel of the valve that controls the entry of Russian gas into the Western European grid.
The new pipeline will bring 27.5 million cubic metres of additional Russian gas to Western Europe each year via a 1,224 km first tunnel linking the St Petersburg region with the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second pipeline should be completed by the end of 2012 and will supply a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, enough to cover all French consumption.
In addition, there is already talk of the possibility of building a third tube along the same route.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge project looks like a victory.
Poland and the Baltic States had strongly opposed the project.
The Nord Stream will in fact allow gas to be supplied directly to Germany, avoiding the overland passage through third countries (Poland and Ukraine).
Suddenly, these two countries lose some of their power: it will be harder for them to influence Russia by threatening to cut off access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare Nord Stream to a "new German-Soviet pact", in reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
I mean, if the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, by supporting the Russian project, has gained greater security of supply.
But the price is a weakening of energy Europe, since the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
In just five years, Russia has succeeded in making its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, large consumers of gas and with increasingly limited reserves, a reality.
"This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that unites us organically", François Fillon confirmed at the inauguration of the pipeline, showing how big gas contracts are both political and economic.
All this explains the wide smiles on the faces of Gazprom executives, many in Lubmin, at the gas arrival point.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical achievement.
The submarine tube is made of steel coated with cement to protect it from the anchors of the ships.
It rests on the seabed, at an average depth of 200 m.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating back to World War II.
"A hundred of them had to be removed or destroyed as a precaution", says Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to step up measures to protect the fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake that weighs as much as 242 Eiffel Towers and is uninterrupted in its entire length: neither by valves nor by maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned in Swedish waters, but the project was abandoned when the Swedes were unwilling to allow a Russian state company to be permanently established at sea off their coast.
"In the event of a breakdown, we will stop the gas flow in less than a minute", says Jens Müller.
In the event of a leak, the gas from the pipeline will therefore be released into the atmosphere.
But the builders consider leakage unlikely, for they have planned joints that are projected to leak every 100,000 years.
The monitoring of the status of the pipeline is ensured by an underwater robot, dragged by a ship, which carries out external inspections, as well as by a device circulating inside the pipeline.
In the shape of a cigar, it is inserted into the inside of the tube, which has a diameter of one meter, and moves with the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of ten feet per second, it provides precise data on possible metal deformations.
The pipeline has been designed to operate for 50 years without any repair.
The gas circulation is ensured simply by pressure.
At the beginning it's 200 bars and at the end it's 100 bars.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leading company is Gazprom, which owns 51% of the shares.
It was joined by E.ON and BASF (15.5% each) and Gasunie and GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have created a joint venture, called Nord Stream, to build and operate the pipeline.
It is based in Zoug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom subsequently leased all gas transmission capacities to Gazprom for a renewable period of 25 years.
"Gazprom will be paid for the full capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported", says Jens Müller.
The construction of the pipeline was financed by 30% of the shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the work is expected to reach 7.4 billion euros for the two pipelines.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment has reached 240 million.
But the minority shareholders are sure that they will not exceed their investment, since Gazprom alone assumes the risk of the costs.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic at Lubmin, on a sandy coast planted with pine trees.
A pair of 15 foot high valves form the gas outlet.
There are sensors that measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas on arrival, before it is transferred to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal has been receiving a million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
At full capacity, it will be three million an hour and in 2012, six million.
Moleskine, a branded notebook.
Created half a century ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to bring people back to the taste for writing.
It has an air of adventure, of hours of writing by candlelight.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognizable, with its black rectangular pastes, its rubber, its broken white leaves, as if aged by time.
However, the Moleskine notebooks with the current look were born... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at that time to launch a design notebook, but distinguished.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant for the company, was in charge of the launch of the new product.
The notebook is inspired by an ancient production technique, mole skin, which refers to a varnished cotton used, among other things, to cover the benches.
This type of notebook was highly valued by writers and travelers.
"Moleskine has adapted an old and forgotten object, an icon of avant-garde artists until the 20th century, to the current taste", says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become the brand manager at Modo Modo.
And he succeeded.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26%, reaching a volume of 12,7 million units sold.
The confidential production of the first years, when only 3,000 notebooks were designed, has been far from complete.
Moleskine goes beyond the Italian borders and exports its products to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to determine the buyer profile, since the notebook attracts businessmen as well as students and professionals.
Like Moleskine, its users are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cultured.
The small Italian company, which started with 12 employees, now has around 100 and, since 2008, has two offices: one in Milan and the other in New York.
It distributes its notebooks in bookstores, from the Fnac to small shops in the city centre, and has been able to impose its identity.
"We have adapted to the times and the need to write, despite the boom of e-mail", explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural firm goes hand in hand with the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand has launched the exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists exhibit their own notebook.
In August, she also launched a notebook with leopard caps, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has diversified its products: bags, diaries, pens, computer cases... The brand covers a wide range of supports.
An enviable success: in the fall of 2006, Modo Modo was acquired by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, thus writing a new page in the history of Moleskine.
Why is the unemployment rate for disabled workers still so high?
About 19% of disabled people are looking for work.
The 15th Employment Week for the Disabled begins today.
Despite a determined public policy implemented since 2005, the unemployment rate among disabled people is twice the average rate: 19%, compared to 9% for the general population.
Discouraging?
"No", says Éric Blanchet, managing director of Adapt, the association which organises the Employment Week for the Disabled.
"The progress made over the past 15 years is considerable.
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not twice but three times higher than the average.
"However, there is still a great deal to be done".
It should be noted that disabled unemployed people still face numerous obstacles to access to employment.
They are usually older: 37% are over 50 (an average of 17%).
They have a low level of qualifications: 80% have not completed secondary school and of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, longterm unemployment is widespread among them: 53% for the disabled, compared with 38% on average.
In other words, there are many issues that make it particularly difficult to return to work and that "are the core of the problem", says Christian Grapin, managing director of Tremplin, an association set up in 1992 to help companies recruit disabled workers.
Those are the objective obstacles.
There are also those that are not mentioned; people's minds move forward, but too slowly.
A study carried out in April by the IMS-Entrepreneur association for the Cité noted that managers surveyed have "a low level of knowledge about disabilities", with an "overrepresentation of people in wheelchairs, physically or intellectually disabled".
The result: private enterprises with more than 20 employees are far from the target of hiring 6% of disabled workers, which was set in a law of... 1987.
According to the latest available figures, which date back to 2008, they reach a ratio of 2,6%.
"We are now at around 3%", says Pierre Blanc, managing director of Agefiph, the body responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not respect this law.
The proof: the number of establishments 'subject to this contribution', as well as the amounts disbursed, decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59 000 to 46 000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which increased contributions, has put a lot of pressure on companies", explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also reflects a real awareness, particularly among large groups".
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of companies with between 20 and 49 employees have disabled employees in their workforce, compared with 82% of companies with between 100 and 199 employees.
Hazard: "A joy"
Ahead of their match against the Blues on Tuesday night (20:45), Eden Hazard and Georges Leekens are delighted with this friendly.
We dare not say that there was any conspiracy between them, but the image is symbolic.
Sitting side by side on the podium of the Stade de France auditorium, Georges Leekens and Eden Hazard have really made up.
