Portugal shows a lot of confidence
Paulo Bento's Portugal are looking forward to their second leg against Bosnia at 22.00 on Tuesday in Lisbon.
In the first leg, both teams lacked realism.
"When these 90 minutes are up, we'll be a happy team and, above all, a happy country".
Paulo Bento is already seen in Poland and Ukraine.
He has no doubt; the Selecçao, which he has led since September 2010, will qualify for the Euro 2012.
Indeed, only 90 minutes separate Portugal from happiness.
But there's a game to play and a rival, Bosnia, to beat.
Considering the first leg (0-0), on Friday in Zenica's hell, it seems obvious that the matter is not decided.
Portugal dominated the game for over an hour, yes, but they couldn't score the valuable goal that would have given them the peace of mind.
"It's a good result, but it also carries a risk, since we haven't scored away from home".
But at home, in the bright Lisbon Stadium, the Portuguese are convinced they will pass, before an audience that should be equally enthusiastic, even if it is clear that the game "is very even", said an optimistic but lucid Bento.
"We hope the game is very evenly matched, but we are completely convinced that we can take the lead", said the 42-year-old Portuguese coach.
"We still have 50% chance of participating in the Euro 2012", has, however, relativised the successor of Carlos Queiroz.
Friday's draw in Bosnia forces the Portuguese to score and win.
The Bosnians could get a draw, although they also need to score.
"It's a good result, but it also carries a risk, since we haven't scored outside the home", Bento laments.
"We are going to play against a team that has a great technical quality and has players with a great individual quality", he added.
As in Zenica, the Portuguese will go with the intention of exerting maximum pressure on the Bosnians from the outset to "not give them time to think".
Good idea, as long as, this time, it's realistic.
